{"title_page": "Some Good News", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 web series}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name = Some Good News\n| image = Some Good News.jpg\n| caption = Some Good News Logo\n| channel_url = UCOe_y6KKvS3PdIfb9q9pGug\n| channel_display_name = SomeGoodNews\n| years_active = 2020\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Talk show]]\n* [[News]]\n}}\n| subscribers = 2 million<!--please update date in stats_update field when you update this-->\n| views = 36.5 million<!--please update date in stats_update field when you update this-->\n| network = None\n| silver_button = yes\n| silver_year = 2020\n| gold_button = yes\n| gold_year = 2020\n| diamond_button = no\n| ruby_button = no\n| red_diamond_button = no\n| stats_update = April 20, 2020\n}}\n\n'''''Some Good News''''' is a 2020 [[web series]] created and hosted by actor and filmmaker [[John Krasinski]]. The show, which is hosted on [[YouTube]], is \"a news show dedicated entirely to good news\" with Krasinski operating inside his home during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Strout\">{{cite news |last1=Strout |first1=Paige |title=Why TV Fans Should Be Watching John Krasinski's 'Some Good News' |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/930011/john-krasinski-some-good-news-reasons-to-watch/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=TV Insider |date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> ''Some Good News'' debuted on March 29, 2020, and as of April 13 had 1.66 million subscribers.<ref name=\"WCVB\">{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018Some Good News\u2019 YouTube series and Big Papi honor staff at Beth Israel Deaconess\n |url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/john-krasinskis-some-good-news-youtube-series-and-big-papi-honor-staff-at-beth-israel-deaconess/32127395# |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Episode 1===\n''Some Good News'' debuted March 29, 2020. Krasinski opened the show by stating, \"We are all going through an incredibly trying time, but, through all the anxiety, through all the confusion, all the isolation, and all the ''[[Tiger King]]'', somehow the human spirit found a way to break through and blow us all away.\"<ref name=\"Jasevi\u010di\u016bt\u0117\">{{cite news |last1=Jasevi\u010di\u016bt\u0117 |first1=And\u017eelika |title=John Krasinski Shares Some Good News, Invites Steve Carell To Lift Up People's Spirits |url=https://www.boredpanda.com/some-good-news-show-the-office-anniversary-john-krasinski-steve-carell/?utm_source=google&utm_medium=organic&utm_campaign=organic |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Bored Panda |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Krasinski's former costar on ''[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]'' [[Steve Carell]] appeared on the show as an \"entertainment correspondent.\" Krasinski also interviewed a 15-year-old cancer survivor named Courtney \"Coco\" Johnson.<ref name=\"Pesce\">{{cite news |last1=Pesce |first1=Nicole Lyn |title=John Krasinski and Steve Carell bring 'Some Good News' in a new YouTube series |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/john-krasinski-and-steve-carell-bring-some-good-news-in-a-new-youtube-series-2020-03-30 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Market Watch |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Episode 1 was 15 minutes 43 seconds. The episode appeared on YouTube's Trending page and was viewed 3.1 million times one day after being uploaded.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Julia |title=The Office\u2019s John Krasinski launched a YouTube channel dedicated to good news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/30/21200161/john-krasinski-youtube-some-good-news-office-steve-carell-michael-scott-coronavirus |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=The Verge |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> It had been viewed over 12 million times by April 5, 2020.<ref name=\"Rahman\">{{cite news |last1=Rahman |first1=Abid |title=John Krasinski Returns With Second Episode of YouTube Show 'Some Good News' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-krasinski-returns-second-episode-some-good-news-1288649 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 2===\nEpisode 2 released April 5, 2020. The episode featured a new introduction, which was created by a viewer.<ref name=\"Molina-Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Molina-Whyte |first1=Linda |title=John Krasinski\u2019s Some Good News brings together original Hamilton cast |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-06/john-krasinski-some-good-news-original-hamilton-cast/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Radio Times |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> In the episode, Krasinski had multiple guest stars, including his wife actress [[Emily Blunt]], actor [[Robert De Niro]], composer [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], and the cast of the musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' (including original performers [[Leslie Odom Jr.]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] and [[Renee Elise Goldsberry]]). He also interviewed a nine-year-old girl named Aubrey who was a \"superfan\" of ''Hamilton'' but was unable to see the show due to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Haylock\">{{cite news |last1=Haylock |first1=Zoe |title=Hamilton Cast Reunion Happens in Separate Rooms |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/john-krasinski-some-good-news-hamilton-cast.html |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Vulture |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> He stated he would fly Aubrey out to the show once the coronavirus was over, but in the meantime arranged for the cast to perform for her from their homes via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]].<ref name=\"Price\">{{cite news |last1=Price |first1=Joe |title=John Krasinski Reunites Original Cast of 'Hamilton' for 'Some Good News' Show |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2020/04/john-krasinski-some-good-news-hamilton-reunion |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Complex |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Ad Age]]'' called the episode \"ridiculously wonderful.\"<ref name=\"Dumenco\">{{cite news |last1=Dumenco |first1=Simon |title=Episode 2 of John Krasinski's 'Some Good News' is Ridiculously Wonderful |url=https://adage.com/article/media/episode-2-john-krasinskis-some-good-news-ridiculously-wonderful/2248386 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Ad Age |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> [[CBN News]] stated \"just like the first episode, this one is definitely worth watching.\"<ref name=\"Goins-Phillips\">{{cite news |last1=Goins-Phillips |first1=Tr\u00e9 |title='Office' Star John Krasinski Keeps the Good News Flowing in Epic Second Episode of 'SGN' |url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/entertainment/2020/april/office-star-john-krasinski-keeps-the-good-news-flowing-in-epic-second-episode-of-sgn |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=CBN News |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> [[NPR]] stated the episode was an \"explosion of good-hearted joy\".<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite news |last1=Thompson |first1=Stephen |title='Hamilton' Cast Reunites For Emily Blunt, John Krasinski And One Lucky 9-Year-Old |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/06/828088183/hamilton-cast-reunites-for-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-and-one-lucky-9-year-old |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=NPR |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 3===\nReleased April 13, 2020, Krasinski and special guest star baseball player [[David Ortiz]] treated five different healthcare workers from [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] in Boston with a trip to [[Fenway Park]] where they were given lifetime season pass tickets to the [[Boston Red Sox]].{{r|WCVB}}<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news |last1=Respers France |first1=Lisa |title=John Krasinski and David Ortiz surprise nurses and respiratory therapists to say thanks |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/13/entertainment/john-krasinski-david-ortiz-hospital-tickets/index.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |agency=[[CNN]]}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' stated \"he managed to create some damn good sports content\u2014and some tears.\"<ref name=\"Traina\">{{cite news |last1=Traina |first1=Jimmy |title=John Krasinski Surprises Hospital Workers With Trip to Fenway, Lifetime Season Tickets: TRAINA THOUGHTS |url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2020/04/13/john-krasinski-some-good-news-surprises-hospital-workers-lifetime-red-sox-tickets |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 4===\nReleased on April 20th, 2020, the episode featured guests [[Chance the Rapper|Chance The Rapper]], [[Brad Pitt]], [[Jonas Brothers|The Jonas Brothers]], [[Billie Eilish]] and her brother [[Finneas Eilish|Finnaes Elish]], and [[Rainn Wilson]]. Pitt provided a weather forecast,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/brad-pitt-hilariously-reports-on-the-weather-for-john-krasinskis-some-good-news-show-145112|title=Watch Brad Pitt's Hilarious Weather Report for John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018SGN'|website=Entertainment Tonight|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/watch-weatherman-brad-pitt-action-john-krasinski-s-some-good-t179313|title=Watch weatherman Brad Pitt in action on John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018Some Good News\u2019|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> and towards the end of the episode, Krasinski, with support from a few of his special guests, created a \"virtual prom\" for teens that were unable to attend their prom due to the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/john-krasinski-prom-2020-recap-some-good-news-episode-4/|title=John Krasinski Recaps His Prom and Chats with Rainn Wilson in \u2018Some Good News\u2019 Episode 4|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=2020-04-20|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://geektyrant.com/news/john-krasinskis-some-good-news-episode-4-throws-prom-2020-for-all-the-seniors-missing-out-with-chance-the-rapper-the-jonas-brothers-and-billy-eilish-stopping-by|title=John Krasinski's SOME GOOD NEWS Episode 4 Throws Prom 2020 With Chance the Rapper, The Jonas Brothers, and Billy Eilish Stopping By|website=GeekTyrant|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Some Good News'' was positively received, including the accompanying [[Twitter]] account Krasinski set up for the show under the handle @somegoodnews.<ref name=\"Gallucci\">{{cite news |last1=Gallucci |first1=Nicole |title=John Krasinski's Some Good News Twitter account will brighten your timeline |url=https://mashable.com/article/john-krasinski-some-good-news-twitter-account/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Mashable |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[TV Insider]] wrote \"...''Some Good News'' has proven how powerful spreading positivity can be. TV fans should put their faith in John Krasinski to deliver what the title of his YouTube series promises amidst the chaos and hardships of life during the COVID-19 pandemic.\"{{r|Strout}}\n\n[[RedState]] called Krasinski a \"[[national treasure]]\" and called the series \"amazing.\"<ref name=\"Morse\">{{cite news |last1=Morse |first1=Brandon |title=John Krasinski Continues to Be a National Treasure With Some Sports Good News |url=https://www.redstate.com/brandon_morse/2020/04/13/john-krasinski-continues-to-prove-to-be-a-national-treasure-with-some-good-news/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=RedState |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://somegoodnews.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|12054924}}\n\n{{John Krasinski}}\n\n[[Category:2020 web series debuts]]\n[[Category:American web series]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 web series}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name = Some Good News\n| image = Some Good News.jpg\n| caption = Some Good News Logo\n| channel_url = UCOe_y6KKvS3PdIfb9q9pGug\n| channel_display_name = SomeGoodNews\n| years_active = 2020\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Talk show]]\n* [[News]]\n}}\n| subscribers = 2 million<!--please update date in stats_update field when you update this-->\n| views = 36.5 million<!--please update date in stats_update field when you update this-->\n| network = None\n| silver_button = yes\n| silver_year = 2020\n| gold_button = yes\n| gold_year = 2020\n| diamond_button = no\n| ruby_button = no\n| red_diamond_button = no\n| stats_update = April 20, 2020\n}}\n\n'''''Some Good News''''' is a 2020 [[web series]] created and hosted by actor and filmmaker [[John Krasinski]]. The show, which is hosted on [[YouTube]], is \"a news show dedicated entirely to good news\" with Krasinski operating inside his home during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Strout\">{{cite news |last1=Strout |first1=Paige |title=Why TV Fans Should Be Watching John Krasinski's 'Some Good News' |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/930011/john-krasinski-some-good-news-reasons-to-watch/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=TV Insider |date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> ''Some Good News'' debuted on March 29, 2020, and as of April 13 had 1.66 million subscribers.<ref name=\"WCVB\">{{cite news |last1= |first1= |title=John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018Some Good News\u2019 YouTube series and Big Papi honor staff at Beth Israel Deaconess\n |url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/john-krasinskis-some-good-news-youtube-series-and-big-papi-honor-staff-at-beth-israel-deaconess/32127395# |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n===Episode 1===\n''Some Good News'' debuted March 29, 2020. Krasinski opened the show by stating, \"We are all going through an incredibly trying time, but, through all the anxiety, through all the confusion, all the isolation, and all the ''[[Tiger King]]'', somehow the human spirit found a way to break through and blow us all away.\"<ref name=\"Jasevi\u010di\u016bt\u0117\">{{cite news |last1=Jasevi\u010di\u016bt\u0117 |first1=And\u017eelika |title=John Krasinski Shares Some Good News, Invites Steve Carell To Lift Up People's Spirits |url=https://www.boredpanda.com/some-good-news-show-the-office-anniversary-john-krasinski-steve-carell/?utm_source=google&utm_medium=organic&utm_campaign=organic |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Bored Panda |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Krasinski's former costar on ''[[The Office (American TV series)|The Office]]'' [[Steve Carell]] appeared on the show as an \"entertainment correspondent.\" Krasinski also interviewed a 15-year-old cancer survivor named Courtney \"Coco\" Johnson.<ref name=\"Pesce\">{{cite news |last1=Pesce |first1=Nicole Lyn |title=John Krasinski and Steve Carell bring 'Some Good News' in a new YouTube series |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/john-krasinski-and-steve-carell-bring-some-good-news-in-a-new-youtube-series-2020-03-30 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Market Watch |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Episode 1 was 15 minutes 43 seconds. The episode appeared on YouTube's Trending page and was viewed 3.1 million times one day after being uploaded.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Julia |title=The Office\u2019s John Krasinski launched a YouTube channel dedicated to good news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/30/21200161/john-krasinski-youtube-some-good-news-office-steve-carell-michael-scott-coronavirus |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=The Verge |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> It had been viewed over 12 million times by April 5, 2020.<ref name=\"Rahman\">{{cite news |last1=Rahman |first1=Abid |title=John Krasinski Returns With Second Episode of YouTube Show 'Some Good News' |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-krasinski-returns-second-episode-some-good-news-1288649 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 2===\nEpisode 2 released April 5, 2020. The episode featured a new introduction, which was created by a viewer.<ref name=\"Molina-Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Molina-Whyte |first1=Linda |title=John Krasinski\u2019s Some Good News brings together original Hamilton cast |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-06/john-krasinski-some-good-news-original-hamilton-cast/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Radio Times |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> In the episode, Krasinski had multiple guest stars, including his wife actress [[Emily Blunt]], actor [[Robert De Niro]], composer [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], and the cast of the musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' (including original performers [[Leslie Odom Jr.]], [[Anthony Ramos (actor)|Anthony Ramos]] and [[Renee Elise Goldsberry]]). He also interviewed a nine-year-old girl named Aubrey who was a \"superfan\" of ''Hamilton'' but was unable to see the show due to the coronavirus.<ref name=\"Haylock\">{{cite news |last1=Haylock |first1=Zoe |title=Hamilton Cast Reunion Happens in Separate Rooms |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/john-krasinski-some-good-news-hamilton-cast.html |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Vulture |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> He stated he would fly Aubrey out to the show once the coronavirus was over, but in the meantime arranged for the cast to perform for her from their homes via [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]].<ref name=\"Price\">{{cite news |last1=Price |first1=Joe |title=John Krasinski Reunites Original Cast of 'Hamilton' for 'Some Good News' Show |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2020/04/john-krasinski-some-good-news-hamilton-reunion |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Complex |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Ad Age]]'' called the episode \"ridiculously wonderful.\"<ref name=\"Dumenco\">{{cite news |last1=Dumenco |first1=Simon |title=Episode 2 of John Krasinski's 'Some Good News' is Ridiculously Wonderful |url=https://adage.com/article/media/episode-2-john-krasinskis-some-good-news-ridiculously-wonderful/2248386 |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Ad Age |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> [[CBN News]] stated \"just like the first episode, this one is definitely worth watching.\"<ref name=\"Goins-Phillips\">{{cite news |last1=Goins-Phillips |first1=Tr\u00e9 |title='Office' Star John Krasinski Keeps the Good News Flowing in Epic Second Episode of 'SGN' |url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/entertainment/2020/april/office-star-john-krasinski-keeps-the-good-news-flowing-in-epic-second-episode-of-sgn |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=CBN News |date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> [[NPR]] stated the episode was an \"explosion of good-hearted joy\".<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite news |last1=Thompson |first1=Stephen |title='Hamilton' Cast Reunites For Emily Blunt, John Krasinski And One Lucky 9-Year-Old |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/06/828088183/hamilton-cast-reunites-for-emily-blunt-john-krasinski-and-one-lucky-9-year-old |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=NPR |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 3===\nReleased April 13, 2020, Krasinski and special guest star baseball player [[David Ortiz]] treated five different healthcare workers from [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center]] in Boston with a trip to [[Fenway Park]] where they were given lifetime season pass tickets to the [[Boston Red Sox]].{{r|WCVB}}<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news |last1=Respers France |first1=Lisa |title=John Krasinski and David Ortiz surprise nurses and respiratory therapists to say thanks |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/13/entertainment/john-krasinski-david-ortiz-hospital-tickets/index.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |agency=[[CNN]]}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' stated \"he managed to create some damn good sports content\u2014and some tears.\"<ref name=\"Traina\">{{cite news |last1=Traina |first1=Jimmy |title=John Krasinski Surprises Hospital Workers With Trip to Fenway, Lifetime Season Tickets: TRAINA THOUGHTS |url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2020/04/13/john-krasinski-some-good-news-surprises-hospital-workers-lifetime-red-sox-tickets |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=Sports Illustrated |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Episode 4===\nReleased on April 20th, 2020, the episode featured guests as [[Chance the Rapper|Chance The Rapper]], [[Brad Pitt]], [[Jonas Brothers|The Jonas Brothers]], [[Billie Eilish]] and her brother [[Finneas Eilish|Finnaes Elish]], and [[Rainn Wilson]]. Pitt provided a weather forecast<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/brad-pitt-hilariously-reports-on-the-weather-for-john-krasinskis-some-good-news-show-145112|title=Watch Brad Pitt's Hilarious Weather Report for John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018SGN'|website=Entertainment Tonight|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/watch-weatherman-brad-pitt-action-john-krasinski-s-some-good-t179313|title=Watch weatherman Brad Pitt in action on John Krasinski\u2019s \u2018Some Good News\u2019|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, and towards the end of the episode, Krasinski, with support from a few of his special guests, created a \"virtual prom\" for teens that were unable to attend their prom due to the pandemic. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/john-krasinski-prom-2020-recap-some-good-news-episode-4/|title=John Krasinski Recaps His Prom and Chats with Rainn Wilson in \u2018Some Good News\u2019 Episode 4|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|date=2020-04-20|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://geektyrant.com/news/john-krasinskis-some-good-news-episode-4-throws-prom-2020-for-all-the-seniors-missing-out-with-chance-the-rapper-the-jonas-brothers-and-billy-eilish-stopping-by|title=John Krasinski's SOME GOOD NEWS Episode 4 Throws Prom 2020 With Chance the Rapper, The Jonas Brothers, and Billy Eilish Stopping By|website=GeekTyrant|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Some Good News'' was positively received, including the accompanying [[Twitter]] account Krasinski set up for the show under the handle @somegoodnews.<ref name=\"Gallucci\">{{cite news |last1=Gallucci |first1=Nicole |title=John Krasinski's Some Good News Twitter account will brighten your timeline |url=https://mashable.com/article/john-krasinski-some-good-news-twitter-account/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |publisher=Mashable |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[TV Insider]] wrote \"...''Some Good News'' has proven how powerful spreading positivity can be. TV fans should put their faith in John Krasinski to deliver what the title of his YouTube series promises amidst the chaos and hardships of life during the COVID-19 pandemic.\"{{r|Strout}}\n\n[[RedState]] called Krasinski a \"[[national treasure]]\" and called the series \"amazing.\"<ref name=\"Morse\">{{cite news |last1=Morse |first1=Brandon |title=John Krasinski Continues to Be a National Treasure With Some Sports Good News |url=https://www.redstate.com/brandon_morse/2020/04/13/john-krasinski-continues-to-prove-to-be-a-national-treasure-with-some-good-news/ |accessdate=April 13, 2020 |newspaper=RedState |date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://somegoodnews.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|12054924}}\n\n{{John Krasinski}}\n\n[[Category:2020 web series debuts]]\n[[Category:American web series]]\n[[Category:Responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisode 4:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Some_Good_News"}
{"title_page": "Doug Holder", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Senator\n| name=Doug Holder\n| image name=State Representative Doug Holder.jpg\n| state_house=Florida\n| state=Florida\n| district=74th\n| term_start=November 20, 2012\n| term_end=November 18, 2014\n| preceded=[[Gary Aubuchon]]\n| succeeded=[[Julio Gonzalez (Florida politician)|Julio Gonzalez]]\n| state_house2=Florida\n| state2=Florida\n| district2=70th\n| term_start2=November 21, 2006\n| term_end2=November 20, 2012\n| preceded2=[[Nancy C. Detert]]\n| succeeded2=[[Darryl Rouson]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1966|12|07}}\n| birth_place=[[Marietta, Georgia]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Middle Tennessee State University]] (B.S.)\n| profession=Small businessman\n| religion=[[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''Doug Holder''' (born on December 7, 1966) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who served as a member of the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from 2006 to 2014, representing the 70th District from 2006 to 2012, and the 74th District, which included [[Englewood, Florida|Englewood]], [[North Port, Florida|North Port]], and [[Venice, Florida|Venice]] in [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], from 2012 to 2014. He is currently a candidate for the [[Florida Senate]] in 2018.\n\n==History==\nHolder attended [[Middle Tennessee State University]], where he received a degree in political science in 1990. While in college, he served as student body president and was the student ambassador for [[George H. W. Bush]] when he visited the campus. Holder moved to the state of [[Florida]] in 1997.\n\n==Florida House of Representatives==\nWhen incumbent [[Florida House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Nancy C. Detert]] was unable to seek re-election in 2006 due to term limits, Holder ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] primary to succeed her in the 70th District, which included most of western [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], stretching from [[Englewood, Florida|Englewood]] to [[Siesta Key, Florida|Siesta Key]], and faced Rory Dubin, Jon Kleiber, and Elizabeth Cuevas-Neunder. He spent nearly $400,000 of his own money on advertising, \"leading some people to accuse Holder...of trying to buy the office and of ignorance of local issues.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20081008/ARTICLE/810080351?tc=ar|title=District 70 candidates talk of less government|date=October 8, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Zac|last=Anderson}}</ref> Holder emerged victorious in the Republican primary, winning 42% of the vote, and moved on to the general election, where he engaged in a contentious campaign with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee, attorney David Shapiro. Though Holder and Shapiro pledged to run positive campaigns, a group supporting Holder, People for a Better Florida Fund, which received a sizable donation from Holder's stepmother, attacked Shapiro for being a \"millionaire trial lawyer\" and for opposing tort reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20061106/NEWS/611060357?tc=ar|title=District 70 campaign finishes on a sour note|date=November 6, 2006|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Todd|last=Ruger}}</ref> Holder narrowly won over Shapiro, winning 51% of the vote to Shapiro's 49%,  a margin of just 756 votes. In 2008, retired dentist Sam Rosenfeld received the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination to challenger Holder's bid for re-election, and though [[Florida Democratic Party|Democrats]] were hopeful that Rosenfeld could defeat Holder, given the closeness of his initial election,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20080410/NEWS/804100480?p=1&tc=pg&tc=ar|title=Democrat steps up to challenge Rep. Holder|date=April 10, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Jeremy|last=Wallace}}</ref> Holder easily dispatched his opponent, winning re-election with 61% of the vote. When Holder ran for re-election in 2010, his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, Nancy Feehan, attacked him over his vote \"to allow the governor and cabinet to permit drilling from 3 to 10 miles from shore,\" which had particular resonance given the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]], which caused Holder to change his mind on offshore oil drilling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20101017/article/10171089|title=Drilling vote is wrinkle in District 70 race|date=October 17, 2010|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Carrie|last=Wells}}</ref> However, despite this fact, Holder managed to repeat his 2008 victory, defeating Feehan with 61% of the vote.\n\nIn 2012, when the legislative districts were reconfigured, Holder was moved to the 74th District, which included most of the territory that he previously represented in [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]] from the 70th District. He did not face any opponents and won final term in the legislature entirely unopposed.\n\n==Florida Senate==\nIn 2013, Holder announced that he would run to succeed [[Florida Senate|State Senator]] [[Nancy Detert]] in the 28th District, which includes western [[Charlotte County, Florida|Charlotte County]] and [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], in 2018, when Detert will be term-limited. Acknowledging that it is unusual to file to run for a position nearly six years in advance of the election, Holder noted, \"If I have competition, it's good for me to get going early.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.heraldtribune.com/2013/02/04/holder-running-for-state-senate/|title=Update: Holder files for race in 2018|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=December 14, 2014|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Jeremy|last=Wallace}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.myfloridahouse.gov/Sections/Representatives/details.aspx?MemberId=4372 Florida House of Representatives - Doug Holder]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holder, Doug}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Florida House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Senator\n| name=Doug Holder\n| image name=State Representative Doug Holder.jpg\n| state_house=Florida\n| state=Florida\n| district=74th\n| term_start=November 20, 2012\n| term_end=November 18, 2014\n| preceded=[[Gary Aubuchon]]\n| succeeded=[[Julio Gonzalez (Florida politician)|Julio Gonzalez]]\n| state_house2=Florida\n| state2=Florida\n| district2=70th\n| term_start2=November 21, 2006\n| term_end2=November 20, 2012\n| preceded2=[[Nancy C. Detert]]\n| succeeded2=[[Darryl Rouson]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1966|12|07}}\n| birth_place=[[Marietta, Georgia]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Middle Tennessee State University]] (B.S.)\n| profession=Small businessman\n| religion=[[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|}}\n\n'''Doug Holder''' (born on December 7, 1966) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who served as a member of the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from 2006 to 2014, representing the 70th District from 2006 to 2012, and the 74th District, which included [[Englewood, Florida|Englewood]], [[North Port, Florida|North Port]], and [[Venice, Florida|Venice]] in [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], from 2012 to 2014. He is currently a candidate for the [[Florida Senate]] in 2018.\n\n==History==\nHolder attended [[Middle Tennessee State University]], where he received a degree in political science in 1990. While in college, he served as Student Body President and was the Student Ambassador for [[George H. W. Bush]] when he visited the campus. Holder moved to the state of [[Florida]] in 1997.\n\n==Florida House of Representatives==\nWhen incumbent [[Florida House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Nancy C. Detert]] was unable to seek re-election in 2006 due to term limits, Holder ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] primary to succeed her in the 70th District, which included most of western [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], stretching from [[Englewood, Florida|Englewood]] to [[Siesta Key, Florida|Siesta Key]], and faced Rory Dubin, Jon Kleiber, and Elizabeth Cuevas-Neunder. He spent nearly $400,000 of his own money on advertising, \"leading some people to accuse Holder...of trying to buy the office and of ignorance of local issues.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20081008/ARTICLE/810080351?tc=ar|title=District 70 candidates talk of less government|date=October 8, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Zac|last=Anderson}}</ref> Holder emerged victorious in the Republican primary, winning 42% of the vote, and moved on to the general election, where he engaged in a contentious campaign with the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee, attorney David Shapiro. Though Holder and Shapiro pledged to run positive campaigns, a group supporting Holder, People for a Better Florida Fund, which received a sizable donation from Holder\u2019s stepmother, attacked Shapiro for being a \"millionaire trial lawyer\" and for opposing tort reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20061106/NEWS/611060357?tc=ar|title=District 70 campaign finishes on a sour note|date=November 6, 2006|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Todd|last=Ruger}}</ref> Holder narrowly won over Shapiro, winning 51% of the vote to Shapiro\u2019s 49%,  a margin of just 756 votes. In 2008, retired dentist Sam Rosenfeld received the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination to challenger Holder\u2019s bid for re-election, and though [[Florida Democratic Party|Democrats]] were hopeful that Rosenfeld could defeat Holder, given the closeness of his initial election,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20080410/NEWS/804100480?p=1&tc=pg&tc=ar|title=Democrat steps up to challenge Rep. Holder|date=April 10, 2008|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Jeremy|last=Wallace}}</ref> Holder easily dispatched his opponent, winning re-election with 61% of the vote. When Holder ran for re-election in 2010, his [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] opponent, Nancy Feehan, attacked him over his vote \"to allow the governor and cabinet to permit drilling from 3 to 10 miles from shore,\" which had particular resonance given the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]], which caused Holder to change his mind on offshore oil drilling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20101017/article/10171089|title=Drilling vote is wrinkle in District 70 race|date=October 17, 2010|accessdate=December 10, 2013|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Carrie|last=Wells}}</ref> However, despite this fact, Holder managed to repeat his 2008 victory, defeating Feehan with 61% of the vote.\n\nIn 2012, when the legislative districts were reconfigured, Holder was moved to the 74th District, which included most of the territory that he previously represented in [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]] from the 70th District. He did not face any opponents and won final term in the legislature entirely unopposed.\n\n==Florida Senate==\nIn 2013, Holder announced that he would run to succeed [[Florida Senate|State Senator]] [[Nancy Detert]] in the 28th District, which includes western [[Charlotte County, Florida|Charlotte County]] and [[Sarasota County, Florida|Sarasota County]], in 2018, when Detert will be term-limited. Acknowledging that it is unusual to file to run for a position nearly six years in advance of the election, Holder noted, \"If I have competition, it's good for me to get going early.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.heraldtribune.com/2013/02/04/holder-running-for-state-senate/|title=Update: Holder files for race in 2018|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=December 14, 2014|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|first=Jeremy|last=Wallace}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.myfloridahouse.gov/Sections/Representatives/details.aspx?MemberId=4372 Florida House of Representatives - Doug Holder]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holder, Doug}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Florida House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doug_Holder"}
{"title_page": "Herod the Great", "text_new": "{{short description|Roman client king of Judea}}\n{{About|the king of Judea from 37\u20134 BC|other rulers also called Herod|Herod (disambiguation){{!}}Herod}}\n{{For|the 1958 film|Herod the Great (film)}}\n{{For|the medieval mystery play|Herod the Great (play)}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name        = Herod\n|title       = King of Judea\n|reign       = 37 BC\u2013 c. 4 BC\n|coronation  =\n|full name   =\n|image       = HerodtheGreat2.jpg\n|predecessor = \n|successor   = {{plainlist|\n*[[Herod Archelaus]]\n*[[Herod Antipas]]\n*[[Philip the Tetrarch]]\n*[[Salome I]]}}\n|spouse      =\n|spouse 1    = Doris\n|spouse 2    = [[Mariamne (second wife of Herod)|Mariamne I]]\n|spouse 3    = [[Mariamne (third wife of Herod)|Mariamne II]]\n|spouse 4    = [[Malthace]]\n|spouse 5    = [[Cleopatra of Jerusalem]]\n|spouse 6    = plus 5 more wives\n|issue       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Antipater (son of Herod the Great)|Antipater&nbsp;II]]\n*[[Alexander, son of Herod|Prince Alexander]]\n*[[Aristobulus IV|Prince Aristobulus&nbsp;IV]]\n*Princess [[Salampsio]]\n*[[Herod&nbsp;II]]\n*[[Herod Antipas]]\n*[[Herod Archelaus]]\n*[[Olympias (Herodian)|Olympias the Herodian]]\n*Prince Herod\n*[[Philip the Tetrarch|Philip]]}}\n|royal house =\n|dynasty     = [[Herodian dynasty]]\n|father      = [[Antipater the Idumaean]]\n|mother      = Cypros\n|birth_date  = c. 74/73 BC\n|birth_place =\n|death_date  = c. 4 BC\n|death_place = [[Jericho]], [[Herodian kingdom|Judea]]\n|burial_date =\n|burial_place= Most likely the [[Herodium]]\n|religion    = [[Second Temple Judaism]]\n}}\n'''Herod''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u025br|\u0259|d}}; {{hebrew Name|\u05d4\u05d5\u05b9\u05e8\u05b0\u05d3\u05d5\u05b9\u05e1|Hordos|H\u014dre\u1e0f\u014ds}}, [[Koine Greek|Greek]]: {{Script|Grek|\u1f29\u03c1\u1ff4\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2}}, ''H\u0113r\u01edd\u0113s'', [[Aramaic]]: {{hebrew|\u05d4\u05b5\u05e8\u05b8\u05d5\u05d3\u05b5\u05e1}} ''H\u0113r\u0101wd\u0113s''; 74/73 [[Before Christ Era|BC]] &ndash; c. 4 BC),<ref name=\"Marshall 2012\"/><ref name=\"Steinmann 2009, pp. 1\"/><ref  name=\"Steinmann 2011\"/><ref name=Filmer/><ref name=\"Perowne 72\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=72}}</ref><ref>Knoblet, Jerry. ''Herod the Great'' (University Press of America, 2005), p. 179.</ref><ref name=\"Perowne 75\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|first=Stewart|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=75}}</ref><ref name=\"Perowne 77\u201379\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=77\u201379}}</ref><ref name=\"Perowne 79\u201380\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=79\u201380}}</ref>  also known as '''Herod the Great''' and '''Herod I''', was a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[client state|client king]] of [[Judea]],<ref name=\"Perowne 92\u201393\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=92\u201393}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last= Peters |first= Francis E. |title= The Monotheists: Jews, Christians, and Muslims in Conflict and Competition, Volume II: The Words and Will of God The Words And Will of God| publisher= Princeton University Press| year= 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| first1= Aryeh |last1= Kasher |first2= Eliezer |last2= Witztum |others= Translation by Karen Gold |title= King Herod: a persecuted persecutor : a case study in psychohistory and psychobiography | publisher= Walter de Gruyter |year= 2007}}</ref> referred to as the [[Herodian Kingdom of Judea|Herodian kingdom]]. The history of his legacy has polarized opinion, as he is known for his colossal building projects throughout Judea, including his renovation of the [[Second Temple#Herod's Temple|Second Temple]] in Jerusalem and the expansion of the [[Temple Mount]] towards its north,<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D15%3Awhiston+chapter%3D11%3Awhiston+section%3D6 15.11.6]\u2013[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D15%3Awhiston+chapter%3D11%3Awhiston+section%3D7 7]); cf. [[Babylonian Talmud]] (''[[Ta'anit (Talmud)|Ta'anit]]'' 23a). Josephus, ''[[The Jewish War]]'' ([http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0148%3Abook%3D1%3Awhiston+chapter%3D21 1.21.1]). Herod the Great rebuilt the Temple sanctuary and expanded the Temple Mount at its north side around the older Temple courts, and \"enclosed an area double the former size.\" Formerly, according to the [[Mishnah]] ([http://www.sefaria.org/Mishnah_Middot.2.1?lang=bi ''Middot'' 2:1]), the Temple Mount had measured 500 cubits x 500 cubits square, and its expansion was done to accommodate the pilgrims.</ref> the [[Tomb of the Patriarchs]] in [[Hebron]], the construction of the port at [[Caesarea Maritima]], the fortress at [[Masada]], and [[Herodium]]. Vital details of his life are recorded in the works of the 1st century [[Common Era|CE]] Roman\u2013Jewish historian [[Josephus]].<ref name=\"Schwartz 59-62\">{{cite book |last=Schwartz |first=Seth |date=2014 |title=The Ancient Jews from Alexander to Muhammad |chapter-url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Y6pkAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA59 |location=[[Cambridge]] |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |chapter=Herod to Florus |pp=59\u201362 |isbn=978-1-107-04127-1}}</ref> Herod also appears in the Christian [[Gospel of Matthew]] as the ruler of Judea who orders the [[Massacre of the Innocents]] at the time of the [[Nativity of Jesus|birth of Jesus]], although a majority of Herod biographers do not believe this event to have occurred.{{sfn|Maier|1998|p=170-171}} Despite his successes, including singlehandedly forging a new aristocracy from practically nothing,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Shaye|title=Ancient Israel: From Abraham to the Roman Destruction of the Temple|publisher=Prentice Hall Biblical Archeological Society|pages=269}}</ref> he has still garnered criticism from various historians. His reign polarizes opinion amongst scholars and historians, some viewing his legacy as evidence of success, and some as a reminder of his tyrannical rule.<ref name=\"Schwartz 59-62\"/>\n\nUpon Herod's death, the Romans divided his kingdom among three of his sons and his sister\u2014[[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]] became [[ethnarch]] of [[Judea]], [[Samaria]], and [[Idumea]], [[Herod Antipas]] became tetrarch of [[Galilee]] and [[Perea (Holy Land)|Peraea]], [[Philip the Tetrarch|Philip]] became tetrarch of territories north and east of the Jordan, and [[Salome I]] was given a [[toparchy]] including the cities of [[Yavne-Yam|Jabneh]], [[Ashdod-Sea|Ashdod]], and [[Phasaelis]].\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Herod coin1.jpg|thumb|Copper coin of Herod, bearing the legend \"\u0392\u0391\u03a3\u0399\u039b\u0395\u03a9\u03a3 \u0397\u03a1\u03a9\u0394\u039f\u03a5\" (\"[[Basileus|Basile\u014ds]] H\u0113r\u014ddou\") on the obverse]]\n\nIt is generally accepted that Herod was born around 73 BC in [[Idumea]], south of Judea.<ref name=\"EBHerod\">{{Cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/263437/Herod |encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |last=Perowne |first=Stewart H. |title=Herod |year=2013 |accessdate=8 May 2013}}</ref>{{failed verification|reason=This source simply states that he was born in 73 BC. This is not necessarily contrary to \"around 74 BC\", but it is contrary to \"around 74 BCE [as opposed to] about 72/71 BC\", as 73 BC is equidistant from 74 BC and 72 BC. Additionally, does the bit behind the paywall say anything about the date's \"general acceptance\"?|date=September 2016}} However, some authors think that he was born in about 72/71 BC.<ref>Steinmann, Andrew \"When Did Herod the Great Reign?\", Novum Testamentum, Volume 51, Number 1, 2009, pp. 1\u201329.<br>Andrew Steinmann, From Abraham to Paul: A Biblical Chronology. (St. Louis, MO: Concordia Pub. House, 2011), pp. 219-256.<br>Filmer, W. E. \"Chronology of the Reign of Herod the Great\", Journal of Theological Studies ns 17 (1966), 283\u2013298.<!-- Could more precise page numbers be given? These are clearly just the pages in which these dissertations appear, not the pages specifically discussing the dating of Herod's birth. --></ref> He was the second son of [[Antipater the Idumaean]], a high-ranking official under [[ethnarch]] [[Hyrcanus II]], and Cypros, a [[Nabatean]]. Herod's father was by descent an [[Edomite]], whose ancestors had converted to [[Judaism]]. Herod was raised as a Jew.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/263437/Herod Herod] at ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'': \"...thus, Herod was, although a practicing Jew, of Arab origin on both sides.\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/print/2008/12/herod/mueller-text|title=National Geographic Magazine - NGM.com|website=ngm.nationalgeographic.com}}</ref><ref name=PersPers>[[Aryeh Kasher]] and Eliezer Witztum, ''King Herod: A Persecuted Persecutor: A Case Study in Psychohistory'', pp 19-23</ref><ref>Jan Rets\u00f6,''The Arabs in Antiquity: Their History from the Assyrians to the Umayyads'', Routledge (2013), p. 374</ref><ref name=Losch>Richard R. Losch, ''All the People in the Bible'', Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing (2008), p. 155</ref>\n\nHerod's rise to power is largely due to his father's good standing relation with [[Julius Caesar]], who entrusted [[Antipater the Idumaean|Antipater]] with the public affairs of Judea.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D14%3Asection%3D143 14.8.5] (14.143)</ref> Herod, Antipater's son, was appointed provincial governor of Galilee in ca. 47 BCE when Herod was about either 25 or 28 years old ([[Greek language|Greek original]]: \"15 years of age\"),<ref>Sch\u00fcrer, Emil, T. Alec. Burkill, Geza Vermes, and Fergus Millar. ''The History of the Jewish People in the Age of Jesus Christ (175 B.C.-A.D. 135)''. Edinburgh: Clark, 1973. pp. 270-275.</ref> and where he faithfully farmed the taxes of that region for the Roman Senate, and where he met with success in ridding that region of bandits.<ref>J. H. Hayes & S. Mandell, ''The Jewish People in Classical Antiquity: From Alexander to Bar Kochba'', [[Westminster John Knox Press]]: Louisville 1998, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=er1Ls6bSQNMC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA101&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false 118]. {{ISBN|0-664-25727-5}}</ref><ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D14%3Asection%3D158 14.9.1\u20132]</ref> Antipater's elder brother, [[Phasael]], served in the same capacity as governor of Jerusalem. During this time, the young Herod cultivated a good relationship with [[Sextus Julius Caesar (governor of Syria)|Sextus Caesar]], the acting Roman governor of Syria, who appointed Herod as general of [[Coelesyria]] and [[Samaria]], greatly expanding his realm of influence.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[De Bello Judaico]]'' (Wars of the Jews) [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0148%3Abook%3D1%3Awhiston+chapter%3D10%3Awhiston+section%3D8 1.10.8]</ref> He enjoyed the backing of Rome, but his brutality was condemned by the [[Sanhedrin]].<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=630&letter=H Herod&nbsp;I] at ''Jewish Encyclopedia'': \"He was of commanding presence; he excelled in physical exercises; he was a skillful diplomatist; and, above all, he was prepared to commit any crime in order to gratify his unbounded ambition.\"</ref> When yet a private man, Herod had determined to punish [[Hyrcanus II|Hyrcanus]] the king, who had once summoned Herod to stand trial for murder, but was restrained from doing so by the intervention of his father and his elder brother. \n\nIn 41 BC, Herod and his brother Phasael were named as [[tetrarchs]] by the Roman leader [[Mark Antony]]. They were placed in this role to support Hyrcanus&nbsp;II. Later, [[Antigonus the Hasmonean|Antigonus]], Hyrcanus' nephew, took the throne from his uncle with [[Pompeian\u2013Parthian invasion of 40 BC|the help]] of the [[Parthian Empire|Parthians]]. Herod fled to Rome to plead with the Romans to restore Hyrcanus&nbsp;II to power. The Romans had a special interest in Judea because their general [[Pompey the Great]] had [[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)|conquered Jerusalem in 63 BC]], thus placing the region in the Roman sphere of influence. In Rome, Herod was unexpectedly appointed [[Herodian Dynasty|King of the Jews]] by the [[Roman Senate]].<ref>Josephus. [[The Jewish War|''The Wars of the Jews'']] [http://earlyjewishwritings.com/text/josephus/war1.html 1.14.4]: [[Mark Antony]] \"then resolved to get him made king of the Jews\u2026told them that it was for their advantage in the [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]] war that Herod should be king; so they all gave their votes for it. And when the senate was separated, Antony and [[Augustus|Caesar]] went out, with Herod between them; while the consul and the rest of the magistrates went before them, in order to offer sacrifices [to the Roman gods], and to lay the decree in the Capitol. Antony also made a feast for Herod on the first day of his reign\".</ref> Josephus puts this in the year of the [[Roman consul|consulship]] of [[Gnaeus Domitius Calvinus|Calvinus]] and Pollio (40 BC), but [[Appian]] places it in 39 BC.<ref name=\"Steinmann 2009, pp. 1\">Steinmann, Andrew \"When Did Herod the Great Reign?\", Novum Testamentum, Volume 51, Number 1, 2009, pp. 1\u201329.</ref> Herod went back to Judea to win his kingdom from Antigonus. Toward the end of the campaign against Antigonus, Herod married the granddaughter of Hyrcanus&nbsp;II, [[Mariamne I|Mariamne]] (known as Mariamne&nbsp;I), who was also a [[Nephew and niece|niece]] of Antigonus. Herod did this in an attempt to secure his claim to the throne and gain some Jewish favor. However, Herod already had a wife, Doris, and a young son, [[Antipater (son of Herod the Great)|Antipater]], and chose therefore to banish Doris and her child.\n\nHerod and Sosius, the governor of Syria, at the behest of [[Mark Antony]], set out with a large army in 37 BC and [[Siege of Jerusalem (37 BC)|captured Jerusalem]], Herod then sending [[Antigonus II Mattathias|Antigonus]] for execution to Mark Antony.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0146%3Abook%3D14%3Asection%3D468 14.16.1] [14.468]; ''[[De Bello Judaico]]'' (The Jewish War) [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0148%3Abook%3D1%3Awhiston+chapter%3D17%3Awhiston+section%3D2 1.17.2] [1.325]</ref> From this moment, Herod took the role as sole ruler of Judea and the title of ''[[basileus]]'' (\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03c2, \"king\") for himself, ushering in the [[Herodian Dynasty]] and ending the [[Hasmonean Dynasty]]. Josephus reports this as being in the year of the consulship of [[Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa|Agrippa]] and [[Lucius Caninius Gallus|Gallus]] (37 BC), but also says that it was exactly 27 years after Jerusalem fell to Pompey, which would indicate 36 BC. [[Cassius Dio]] also reports that in 37 BCE \"the Romans accomplished nothing worthy of note\" in the area.<ref>[[Cassius Dio|Dio]], ''Roman History'' 49.23.1\u20132.</ref> According to Josephus, Herod ruled for 37 years, 34 of them after capturing Jerusalem.\n[[File:Jerusalem Modell BW 2.JPG|thumb|Model of Herod's Temple]]\n\nAs some believe Herod's family were converts to Judaism, his religious commitment was questioned by some elements of Jewish society.<ref name=psalm>{{cite journal|title=Herod the Great, Sosius, and the Siege of Jerusalem (37 B.C.) in Psalm of Solomon 17|first=Kenneth|last=Atkinson|journal=Novum Testamentum|volume=38|issue=4|date=October 1996|pages=312\u2013322|publisher=Brill|jstor=1560892|doi=10.1163/1568536962613216}}</ref> When [[John Hyrcanus]] conquered the region of Idumaea (the [[Edom]] of the [[Hebrew Bible]]) in 140\u2013130 BC, he required all Idumaeans to obey [[613 Commandments|Jewish law]] or to leave; most Idumaeans thus converted to Judaism, which meant that they had to be [[Circumcision in the Bible|circumcised]],<ref>[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=514&letter=C&search=Circumcision#1790 Circumcision: Circumcision Necessary or Not?] at ''Jewish Encyclopedia'': \"The rigorous [[Shammai]]te view, voiced in the [[Book of Jubilees]] (l.c.), prevailed in the time of [[John Hyrcanus|King John Hyrcanus]], who forced the [[Abrahamic covenant|Abrahamic rite]] upon the Idumeans, and in that of King Aristobulus, who made the Itureans undergo circumcision (Josephus, \"Ant.\" xiii. 9, \u00a7 1; 11, \u00a7 3).\"</ref> and many had intermarried with the Jews and adopted their customs.<ref>\"Herod I\". ''[[Encyclopaedia Judaica]]''. (CD-ROM Edition Version 1.0). Ed. [[Cecil Roth]]. Keter Publishing House. {{ISBN|965-07-0665-8}}</ref> While Herod publicly identified himself as a Jew and was considered as such by some,<ref>Josephus, ''Wars'', 2.13. \"There was also another disturbance at Caesarea, - those Jews who were mixed with the Syrians that lived there rising a tumult against them. The Jews pretended that the city was theirs, and said that he who built it was a Jew, meaning King Herod. The Syrians confessed also that its builder was a Jew; but they still said, however, that the city was a Grecian city; for that he who set up statues and temples in it could not design it for Jews.\"</ref> this religious identification was undermined by the decadent lifestyle of the [[Herodians]], which would have earned them the antipathy of observant Jews.<ref>[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=630&letter=H&search=Herod%20the%20Great#1684 Herod I: Opposition of the Pious] at ''Jewish Encyclopedia'': \"All the worldly pomp and splendor which made Herod popular among the pagans, however, rendered him abhorrent to the Jews, who could not forgive him for insulting their religious feelings by forcing upon them heathen games and combats with wild animals\".</ref>\n\nHerod later executed several members of his own family, including his wife [[Mariamne&nbsp;I]].<ref name=Losch/>\n\n==Reign in Judea==\nHerod's rule marked a new beginning in the history of Judea. Judea had been ruled autonomously by the [[Hasmonean dynasty|Hasmonean kings]] from 140 BC until 63 BC. The Hasmonean kings retained their titles, but became clients of Rome after the conquest by Pompey in 63 BC. Herod overthrew the Hasmonean [[Antigonus II Mattathias|Antigonus]] in a three-year-long war between 37 and 34 BC, ruled under Roman overlordship until his death ca. 4 BCE, and officially passed on the throne to his sons, thus establishing his own, so-called [[Herodian dynasty|Herodian]] dynasty.\n\nHerod was granted the title of \"King of Judea\" by the [[Roman Senate]].<ref>[http://earlyjewishwritings.com/text/josephus/war1.html Jewish War 1].14.4: [[Mark Antony]] \" ...then resolved to get him made king of the Jews ... told them that it was for their advantage in the [[Roman\u2013Parthian Wars|Parthian war]] that Herod should be king; so they all gave their votes for it. And when the senate was separated{{clarify|date=December 2015}}, Antony and [[Augustus|Caesar]] went out, with Herod between them; while the [[consul]] and the rest of the [[magistrates]] went before them, in order to offer sacrifices [to the Roman gods], and to lay the decree in the Capitol. Antony also made a feast for Herod on the first day of his reign.\"</ref> As such, he was a vassal of the Roman Empire, expected to support the interests of his Roman patrons. Nonetheless, just when Herod obtained leadership in Judea, his rule faced two threats. The first threat came from his mother-in-law Alexandra, who sought to regain power for her family, the Hasmoneans,<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|first=Stewart|publisher=Sutton Publishing Limited|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=United Kingdom|pages=70}}</ref> whose dynasty Herod had overthrown in 37 BC.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ancient Israel: From Abraham to the Roman Destruction of the Temple|last=Shanks|first=Hershel|publisher=Biblical Archaeology Society|year=2011|isbn=|location=Washington DC|pages=267}}</ref> In the same year, [[Cleopatra]] married the Roman leader Antony.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=67}}</ref>  Recognizing Cleopatra's influence over Antony, Alexandra asked Cleopatra for aid in making Aristobulus III the High Priest.<ref name=\":02\" /> As a member of the Hasmonean family, Aristobulus III might partially repair the fortunes of the Hasmoneans if made High Priest.<ref name=\":02\" /> Alexandra's request was made, but Cleopatra urged Alexandra to leave Judea with Aristobulus III and visit Antony.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Herod the Great|last=Perowne|year=2003|isbn=0-7509-3273-2|location=|pages=71}}</ref> Herod received word of this plot, and feared that if Antony met Aristobolus III in person he might name Aristobulus III King of Judea.<ref name=\":22\" /> This concern induced Herod, in 35 BC, to order the assassination of Aristobulus, ending this first threat to Herod's throne.<ref name=\"Perowne 72\"/> The marriage of 37 BCE also sparked a power struggle between Roman leaders Octavian, who would later be called [[Augustus]], and [[Mark Antony|Antony]].<ref name=\":12\" /> Herod, owing his throne to Rome, had to pick a side, and he chose Antony.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|title=Ancient Israel|last=Shanks|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=270}}</ref> In 31 BC at Actium, Antony lost to Octavian, posing a second threat to Herod's rule.<ref name=\"Perowne 75\"/> Herod had to regain Octavian's support if he was to keep his throne.<ref name=\":32\" /> At Rhodes in 31 BC, Herod, through his ability to keep Judea open to Rome as a link to the wealth of Syria and Egypt, and ability to defend the frontier, convinced Octavian that he would be loyal to him.<ref name=\"Perowne 77\u201379\"/><ref name=\"Perowne 79\u201380\"/><ref name=\"Perowne 92\u201393\"/> Herod continued to rule his subjects as he saw fit. Despite the autonomy afforded to Herod in his internal reign over Judea, restrictions were placed upon him in his relations with other kingdoms.<ref name=\"Roman Domination\">Cohen, Shaye. \"Roman Domination: The Jewish Revolt and the Destruction of the Second Temple,\" in ''Ancient Israel'', ed. Hershel Shanks. (Biblical Archaeology Society, 1999), p. 270.</ref>\n\nHerod's support from the Roman Empire was a major factor in enabling him to maintain his authority over Judea. There have been mixed interpretations concerning Herod's popularity during his reign. In ''The Jewish War'', [[Josephus]] characterizes Herod's rule in generally favorable terms, and gives Herod the benefit of the doubt for the infamous events that took place during his reign. However, in his later work, ''Jewish Antiquities'', Josephus emphasizes the tyrannical authority that many scholars have come to associate with Herod's reign.<ref name=\"SCohen271\">Cohen, Shaye. \"Roman Domination: The Jewish Revolt and the Destruction of the Second Temple,\" in ''Ancient Israel'', ed. Hershel Shanks. (Biblical Archaeology Society, 1999), p. 271.</ref>\n\nHerod's despotic rule has been demonstrated by many of his security measures aimed at suppressing the contempt his people, especially Jews, had towards him. For instance, it has been suggested that Herod used secret police to monitor and report the feelings of the general populace towards him. He sought to prohibit protests, and had opponents removed by force.<ref name=\"SCohen271\"/> He had a bodyguard of 2,000 soldiers.<ref name=Guard>{{cite book |last=Rocca |first=Samuel |authorlink= |year=2009 |title=The Army of Herod the Great |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=znRtCb6mXLIC |location= |publisher=[[Osprey Publishing]] |pages=15\u201316 |isbn=978-1-8460-3206-6 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref> Josephus describes various units of Herod's personal guard taking part in Herod's funeral, including the ''Doryphnoroi'', and a [[Thracians|Thracian]], [[Celts|Celtic]] (probably [[Gauls|Gallic]]) and [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] contingent.<ref name=Guard/> While the term ''Doryphnoroi'' does not have an ethnic connotation, the unit was probably composed of distinguished veteran soldiers and young men from the most influential Jewish families.<ref name=Guard/> Thracians had served in the Jewish armies since the Hasmonean dynasty, while the Celtic contingent were former bodyguards of [[Cleopatra]] given as a gift by Augustus to Herod following the [[Battle of Actium]].<ref name=Guard/> The Germanic contingent was modeled upon Augustus's personal bodyguard, the ''[[Imperial German Bodyguard (Roman)|Germani Corporis Custodes]]'', responsible for guarding the palace.<ref name=Guard/>\n\nHerod spent lavish sums on his various building projects and generous gifts to other dominions, including Rome itself. His buildings were very large, ambitious projects. Herod was responsible for the construction of the Temple Mount, a portion of which remains today as the Western Wall. In addition, Herod also used the latest technology in [[hydraulic cement]] and underwater construction to build the harbor at [[Caesarea]].<ref name=\"Roman Domination\" /> While Herod's zeal for building transformed Judea, his motives were not selfless. Although he built fortresses ([[Masada]], [[Herodium]], Alexandrium, Hyrcania, and [[Machaerus]]) in which he and his family could take refuge in case of insurrection, these vast projects were also intended to gain the support of the Jews and improve his reputation as a leader.<ref name=\"CohenShaye\">Cohen, Shaye. \"Roman Domination: The Jewish Revolt and the Destruction of the Second Temple,\" in ''Ancient Israel'', ed. Hershel Shanks. (Biblical Archaeology Society, 1999), pp. 269\u2013273.</ref>  Herod also built Sebaste and other pagan cities because he wanted to appeal to the country's substantial pagan population.<ref name=\"Roman Domination\" /> In order to fund these projects, Herod utilized a Hasmonean taxation system that heavily burdened the Judean people. Nevertheless, these enterprises brought employment and opportunities for the people's provision.<ref name=\"AJLevine\">Levine, Amy-Jill. \"Visions of Kingdoms: From Pompey to the First Jewish Revolt,\" in ''The Oxford History of the Biblical World'', ed. Michael D. Coogan. (New York: Oxford University Press, 1998), p. 357.</ref> In some instances, Herod took it upon himself to provide for his people in times of need, such as during a severe famine that occurred in 25 BCE.<ref>Jagersma, Henk. ''A History of Israel from Alexander the Great to Bar Kochba'', trans. John Bowden (London: SCM Press Ltd, 1985), p. 107.</ref>\n\nAlthough he made many attempts at conforming to traditional Jewish laws, there were more instances where Herod was insensitive, which constitutes one of the major Jewish complaints towards Herod as highlighted in Jewish Antiquities. In Jerusalem, Herod introduced foreign forms of entertainment, and erected a golden eagle at the entrance of the Temple, which suggested a greater interest in the welfare of Rome than of Jews.<ref name=\"AJLevine\"/> Herod's taxes garnered a bad reputation\u2014his constant concern for his reputation led him to make frequent, expensive gifts, increasingly emptying the kingdom's coffers, and such lavish spending upset his Jewish subjects.<ref name=\"CohenShaye\" /> The two major Jewish sects of the day, the [[Pharisees]] and the [[Sadducees]], both showed opposition to Herod. The Pharisees were discontented because Herod disregarded many of their demands with respect to the Temple's construction. The Sadducees, who were closely associated with priestly responsibilities in the Temple, opposed Herod because he replaced their high priests with outsiders from [[Babylonia]] and Alexandria, in an effort to gain support from the Jewish Diaspora.<ref>Schiffman, Lawrence H. \"The Jewish\u2013Christian Schism,\" in ''From Text to Tradition: A History of Second Temple and Rabbinic Judaism'' (Hoboken: Ktav Publishing House, 1991), p. 145.</ref> Herod's outreach efforts gained him little, and at the end of his reign anger and dissatisfaction were common amongst Jews. Heavy outbreaks of violence and riots followed Herod's death in many cities, including Jerusalem, as pent-up resentments boiled over. The scope of the disturbances sparked hopes that the Jews of Judea might some day overthrow the Roman overlords, hopes reawakened decades later in the outbreak of the [[First Jewish\u2013Roman War|Great Revolt of 70 CE]].<ref name=\"CohenShaye\" />\n\n==Architectural achievements==\n{{Main|Herodian architecture}}\n\nHerod's most famous and ambitious project was the expansion of the [[Second Temple]] in Jerusalem.  Herod's rebuilding of the Second Temple in Jerusalem was done so that he would \"have a capital city worthy of his dignity and grandeur\"<ref name=\"Roman Domination\" /> and with this reconstruction Herod hoped to gain more support from the Jews.<ref name=\"Roman Domination\" /> Recent findings suggest that the Temple Mount walls and [[Robinson's Arch]] may not have been completed until at least 20 years after his death, during the reign of [[Herod Agrippa II]].<ref name=Western>{{cite web|title=Building the Western Wall: Herod Began it but Didn't Finish it (december 2011)|url=http://www.antiquities.org.il/Article_eng.aspx?sec_id=25&subj_id=240&id=1882&hist=1|publisher=Israel Antiquities Authority|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the 18th year of his reign (20\u201319 BC), Herod rebuilt the Temple on \"a more magnificent scale\".<ref name=temple>[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=123&letter=T&search=Herod's%20Temple Temple of Herod] at ''Jewish Encyclopedia''</ref>  Although work on out-buildings and courts continued for another 80 years, the new Temple was finished in a year and a half.<ref>Graetz, Heinrich (1893) \"History of the Jews: From the Reign of Hyrcanus (135 BC) to the Completion of the Babylonian Talmud (500 AD)\", Cosimo Books, New York, Volume 2, 2009 ed, p.109</ref> To comply with religious law, Herod employed 1,000 priests as masons and carpenters in the rebuilding.<ref name=temple/> The finished temple, which was destroyed in 70 AD, is sometimes referred to as [[Herod's Temple]]. Today, only the four retaining walls remain standing, including the [[Western Wall]]. These walls created a flat platform (the Temple Mount) upon which the Temple was then constructed.\n\nHerod's other achievements include the development of water supplies for Jerusalem, building fortresses such as [[Masada]] and [[Herodium]], and founding new cities such as [[Caesarea Maritima]] and the enclosures of [[Cave of the Patriarchs]] and [[Mamre]] in [[Hebron]]. He and Cleopatra owned a monopoly over the extraction of [[asphalt]] from the Dead Sea, which was used in shipbuilding. He leased [[copper]] mines on [[Cyprus]] from the Roman emperor.\n\n==New Testament references==\n{{Main|Massacre of the Innocents}}\n[[File:Schnorr von Carolsfeld Bibel in Bildern 1860 172.png|thumbnail|Massacre of the Innocents by [[Julius Schnorr von Karolsfeld]], 1860]]\nHerod appears in the [[Gospel of Matthew]],<ref>{{bibleverse-nb||Matthew|2:1\u201323|NRSV}}</ref> which describes an event known as the [[Massacre of the Innocents]]. According to this account, after the birth of [[Jesus]], [[Biblical magi|some magi from the East]] visited Herod to inquire the whereabouts of \"the one having been born king of the Jews\", because they had seen his star in the east (or, according to certain translations, at its rising) and therefore wanted to pay him homage. Herod, as King of the Jews, was alarmed at the prospect of a usurper. Herod assembled the chief priests and scribes of the people and asked them where the \"Anointed One\" (the [[Messiah]], Greek: \u1f49 \u03a7\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03cc\u03c2, ''ho Christos'') was to be born. They answered, in [[Bethlehem]], citing [[Jesus and Messianic prophecy#Micah 5:2|Micah 5:2]]. Herod therefore sent the magi to Bethlehem, instructing them to search for the child and, after they had found him, to \"report to me, so that I too may go and worship him\". However, after they had found Jesus, they were warned in a dream not to report back to Herod. Similarly, [[Saint Joseph|Joseph]] was warned in a dream that Herod intended to kill Jesus, so he and his family fled to Egypt. When Herod realized he had been outwitted, he gave orders to kill all boys of the age of two and under in Bethlehem and its vicinity. Joseph and his family stayed in Egypt until Herod's death, then moved to [[Nazareth]] in Galilee to avoid living under Herod's son [[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]].\n\nMost modern biographers of Herod, and probably a majority of biblical scholars, dismiss Matthew's story as an invention.<ref>{{Cite book| last      = Maier| first     = Paul L.| chapter   = Herod and the Infants of Bethlehem| editor1-last  = Summers | editor1-first = Ray | editor2-last  = Vardaman| editor2-first = Jerry | title     = Chronos, Kairos, Christos II: Chronological, Nativity, and Religious Studies in Memory of Ray Summers| publisher = Mercer University Press| year      = 1998| chapter-url       = https://books.google.com/?id=mWnYvI5RdLMC&pg=PA169&dq=Herod+and+the+Infants+of+Bethlehem#v=onepage&q=Herod%20and%20the%20Infants%20of%20Bethlehem&f=false| pages       = 170\u2013171| isbn      = 978-0865545823| ref       = harv}}</ref> Contemporary non-biblical sources, including Herod's friend and personal historian, Nicolas of Damascus, provide no corroboration for Matthew's account of the massacre,<ref name=sanders>[[E. P. Sanders|Sanders, E. P.]] (1994). ''The Historical Figure of Jesus''. Viking Adult. pp. 87\u201388.</ref> and it is not mentioned in the [[Gospel of Luke]].  Classical historian [[Michael Grant (classicist)|Michael Grant]] states \u201c[t]he tale is not history but myth or folk-lore\u201d,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Grant |first1=Michael |title=Herod the Great |date=1971 |publisher=American Heritage Press |isbn=978-0070240735 |url=https://archive.org/details/herodgreat00gran_0 }}</ref> while Peter Richardson notes that the story's absence from the Gospel of Luke and the accounts of Josephus \"work[s] against the account's accuracy\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Richardson |first=Peter |title=Herod King of the Jews and Friend of the Romans |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |year=1996 |p=298 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MWTakr1BbvkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=richardson+herod#v=onepage&q=massacre&f=false|isbn=9781570031366 }}</ref> Richardson suggests that the event in Matthew's gospel was inspired by Herod's murder of his own sons.<ref>{{cite book|last=Richardson |first=Peter |title=Herod King of the Jews and Friend of the Romans |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |year=1996 |p=288 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MWTakr1BbvkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=richardson+herod#v=snippet&q=massacred&f=false|isbn=9781570031366 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Herod coin.jpg|thumb|left|[[Herodian coinage|Coin of Herod the Great]]]]\n\nHerod died in [[Jericho]],<ref name=\"EBHerod\"/> after an excruciatingly painful, putrefying illness of uncertain cause, known to posterity as \"Herod's Evil\".<ref>[http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/196/what-loathsome-disease-did-king-herod-die-of What loathsome disease did King Herod die of?], ''[[The Straight Dope]]'', November 23, 1979</ref><ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'',  [http://www.ccel.org/j/josephus/works/ant-17.htm 17.6.5]</ref> Josephus states that the pain of his illness led Herod to attempt suicide by stabbing, and that the attempt was thwarted by his cousin.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', [http://www.ccel.org/j/josephus/works/ant-17.htm 17.7]</ref> In some much later narratives and depictions, the attempt succeeds; for example, in the 12th-century [[Eadwine Psalter]].<ref>Zarnecki, George and others; ''English Romanesque Art, 1066\u20131200'', p. 111, 1984, Arts Council of Great Britain, {{ISBN|0728703866}}</ref> Other medieval dramatizations, such as the [[Ordo Rachelis]], follow Josephus' account.<ref>Murray, Alexander, ''Suicide in the Middle Ages: Volume 2: The Curse on Self-Murder'', 2000, Oxford University Press, {{ISBN|0191613991|978-0191613999}}</ref><!--Based on Josephus' descriptions, one medical expert has diagnosed Herod's cause of death as [[chronic kidney disease]] complicated by [[Fournier's gangrene]].<ref>CNN.com \u2013 Health (25 January 2002). [http://edition.cnn.com/2002/HEALTH/conditions/01/25/king.herod/ Mystery of Herod's death 'solved'] ''CNN'' Archives, 2002. Accessed 30 January 2013.</ref>-->\nMost scholarship concerning the date of Herod's death follows [[Emil Sch\u00fcrer]]'s calculations, which revised a traditional death date of 1 BCE to 4 BCE.<ref>[[Emil Sch\u00fcrer|Sch\u00fcrer, Emil]]. ''A History of the Jewish People in the Time of Jesus Christ'', Vol. I, Herod the Great pp. 400-467, New York, Scribner's, 1896. [https://archive.org/details/historyofjewishp01sch/]</ref><ref name=\"Marshall 2012\"/><ref name=\"Steinmann 2011\"/><ref name=\"Barnes date\">Barnes, Timothy David. \"The Date of Herod's Death,\" ''Journal of Theological Studies'' ns 19 (1968), 204\u2013219</ref><ref name=Bernegger>Bernegger, P. M. \"Affirmation of Herod's Death in 4 B.C.\", ''Journal of Theological Studies'' ns 34 (1983), 526\u2013531.</ref> Two of Herod's sons, Archelaus and [[Philip the Tetrarch]], dated their rule from 4&nbsp;BCE,<ref>Josephus, ''Wars'', 1.631\u2013632.</ref> though Archelaus apparently held royal authority during Herod's lifetime.<ref>Josephus, ''Wars'', 2.26.</ref> Philip's reign would last for 37 years, until his death in the 20th year of [[Tiberius]] (34 CE), which implies his accession as 4&nbsp;BCE.<ref>[[Harold Hoehner|Hoehner, Harold]]. ''Herod Antipas'', (Zondervan, 1980) p.251.</ref> Some scholars support the traditional date of 1&nbsp;BCE for Herod's death.<ref>Edwards, Ormond. \"Herodian Chronology\", ''[[Palestine Exploration Quarterly]]'' 114 (1982) 29\u201342</ref><ref>Keresztes, Paul. ''Imperial Rome and the Christians: From Herod the Great to About 200 AD'' (Lanham, Maryland: University Press of America, 1989), pp. 1\u201343.</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=The Nativity and Herod's Death| journal= Chronos, Kairos, Christos: Nativity and Chronological Studies Presented to Jack Finegan |editor1-first=Jerry |editor1-last= Vardaman |editor2-first= Edwin M. |editor2-last= Yamauchi |location= Winona Lake, Indiana |publisher= Eisenbrauns |year= 1989| pages= 85\u201392}}</ref><ref>Finegan, Jack. [http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/brill/not/2009/00000051/00000001/art00001 ''Handbook of Biblical Chronology''], Rev. ed. (Peabody, MA: Hendrickson, 1998) 300, \u00a7516.</ref> Filmer and Steinmann, for example, propose that Herod died in 1 BCE, and that his heirs backdated their reigns to 4 or 3 BCE to assert an overlapping with Herod's rule, and bolster their own legitimacy.<ref name=\"Steinmann 2009, pp. 1\"/><ref  name=\"Steinmann 2011\">Steinmann, Andrew. ''From Abraham to Paul: A Biblical Chronology'' (St. Louis: Concordia, 2011),  pp. 235\u2013238.</ref><ref name=Filmer>Filmer, W. E. \"Chronology of the Reign of Herod the Great\", ''[[Journal of Theological Studies]]'' ns 17 (1966), 283\u2013298.</ref><ref name=\"Marshall 2012\">Marshall, Taylor. ''The Eternal City'' (Dallas: St. John, 2012), pp. 35\u201365.</ref> In Josephus' account, Herod's death was preceded by a [[lunar eclipse]] and followed by [[Passover]].<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 17.6.4</ref> A partial eclipse best observed from the west coast of Africa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/5MCLEmap/-0099-0000/LE-0003-03-13P.gif|title=Lunar eclipse of March 13, 4 BCE}}</ref> took place on March 13, 4&nbsp;BCE, about 29 days before Passover. Whilst this eclipse has been suggested as the one referred to by Josephus,<ref name=Bernegger /> there were other eclipses during this period, with proponents of 5&nbsp;BCE<ref name=\"Barnes date\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/LEcat5/LE-0099-0000.html|title=Catalog of Lunar Eclipses: -0099 to 0000|website=eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov}}</ref> and the two eclipses of 1 BCE occurring January 10, being the most spectacular total lunar eclipse and December 29, another only partial eclipse.<ref name=\"Filmer\"/><ref name=Steinmann>Steinmann, Andrew. [http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/brilleclipses /not/2009/00000051/00000001/art00001 \"When Did Herod the Great Reign?\"]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Novum Testamentum'', Volume 51, Number 1, 2009, pp. 1\u201329.</ref><ref name=\"Marshall 2012\"/>\n[[File:Herodian tetrachy.png|thumb|The Division of Herod's Kingdom: <br>{{legend inline|blue|Territory under [[Herod Archelaus]]}}<br />{{legend inline|purple|Territory under [[Herod Antipas]]}}<br />{{legend inline|orange|Territory under [[Philip the Tetrarch]]}}<br />{{legend inline|salmon|[[Yavne|Jamnia]] under [[Salome I]]}}.]]\n[[File:Bronze coin of Herod the Star minted at Samaria.jpg|thumb|Bronze coin of Herod the Great, minted at [[Samaria]].]]\nScholars agree Herod suffered throughout his lifetime from depression and paranoia.<ref>http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/876330.htm  {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Josephus stated that Herod was so concerned that no one would mourn his death, that he commanded a large group of distinguished men to come to Jericho, and he gave an order that they should be killed at the time of his death so that the displays of grief that he craved would take place;<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 17.6.174\u2013175.</ref> but his son Archelaus and his sister [[Salome I|Salome]] did not carry out this wish.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 17.8.193.</ref>\n\n=== Successors ===\nAugustus respected the terms of Herod's will, which stipulated the division of Herod's kingdom among three of his sons.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 17.12.317\u2013319. Augustus \"appointed [[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]], not indeed to be the king of the whole country, but [[ethnarch]] of one half of that which had been subject to Herod, and promised to give him the royal dignity hereafter, if he governed his part virtuously. But as for the other half, he divided it into two parts, and gave it to two other of Herod's sons, to [[Herod Philip II|Philip]] and to [[Herod Antipas]], that Herod Antipas who disputed with [[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]] for the whole kingdom. Now, to him it was that [[Perea (Holy Land)|Perea]] and [[Galilee]] paid their tribute, which amounted annually to two hundred talents, while [[Batanea]] with [[Trachonitis]], as well as [[Auranitis]], with a certain part of what was called House of Lenodorus, paid the tribute of one hundred talents to [[Herod Philip II|Philip]]; but [[Idumea]], and [[Judea]], and the country of [[Samaria]], paid tribute to [[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]], but had now a fourth part of that tribute taken off by the order of Caesar, who decreed them that mitigation, because they did not join in this revolt with the rest of the multitude.\"</ref>  Augustus recognised Herod's son [[Herod Archelaus]] as [[ethnarch]] of Judea, [[Samaria]], and [[Idumea]]  to 6&nbsp;CE, referred to as the [[Tetrarchy (Judea)|tetrarchy of Judea]]. Augustus then judged Archelaus incompetent to rule, removed him from power, and combined the provinces of Samaria, Judea proper, and Idumea into [[Iudaea province]].<ref>Ben-Sasson, H. H. ''A History of the Jewish People'', Harvard University Press, 1976, {{ISBN|0-674-39731-2}}, p. 246: \"When Archelaus was deposed from the ethnarchy in 6&nbsp;CE, Judea proper, Samaria and Idumea were converted into a Roman province under the name Iudaea.\"</ref> This enlarged province was ruled by a [[Prefect#Ancient Rome|prefect]] until the year 41. As to Herod's other sons,  [[Herod Antipas]]  was tetrarch of [[Galilee]] and [[Perea (Holy Land)|Peraea]] from Herod's death to 39&nbsp;CE when he was deposed and exiled; [[Philip the Tetrarch|Philip]] became tetrarch of territories north and east of the Jordan and ruled until his death in 34&nbsp;CE.\n\n==Herod's tomb==\n[[File:Herodium from above 2.jpg|thumb|Aerial photo of [[Herodium]] from the southwest]]\n\nThe location of Herod's tomb is documented by [[Josephus]], who writes, \"And the body was carried two hundred [[furlong]]s, to Herodium, where he had given order to be buried.\"<ref>Josephus, ''Wars'', 5.33.1.</ref> Professor [[Ehud Netzer]], an archaeologist from the [[Hebrew University]], read the writings of Josephus and focused his search on the vicinity of the pool and its surroundings. An article in the ''New York Times'' states,\n<blockquote>Lower [[Herodium]] consists of the remains of a large palace, a race track, service quarters, and a monumental building whose function is still a mystery. Perhaps, says Ehud Netzer, who excavated the site, it is Herod's [[mausoleum]]. Next to it is a pool, almost twice as large as modern [[Olympic-size pool]]s.<ref>Rosovsky, Nitza. (24 April 1983) [https://www.nytimes.com/1983/04/24/travel/discovering-herod-s-israel.html \"Discovering Herod's Israel\"], ''[[The New York Times]]''. Accessed 7 May 2013.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIt took thirty-five years for Netzer to identify the exact location, but on May 7, 2007, an [[Israel]]i team of [[archeology|archaeologists]] of Hebrew University, led by Netzer, announced they had discovered the tomb.<ref>{{cite news| title=Archeologist: King Herod's tomb desecrated, but discovery 'high point' |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/archeologist-king-herod-s-tomb-desecrated-but-discovery-high-point-1.219914 |newspaper= [[Haaretz]] | author1= Haaretz Staff\t|first2= Amiram |last2= Barkat | date=7 May 2007  | accessdate= 7 May 2013}}</ref><ref>Associated Press (7 May 2007). [http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,270575,00.html \"Israeli Archaeologist Finds Tomb of King Herod\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206050422/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,270575,00.html |date=2008-12-06 }}, [[Fox News Channel|''FOX News'']], Accessed 7 May 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.isracast.com/Articles/Article.aspx?ID=634 \"Herod's Tomb Discovered\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814131042/http://www.isracast.com/Articles/Article.aspx?ID=634 |date=2007-08-14 }} ''IsraCast'', May 8, 2007. Accessed 7 May 2013.</ref><ref>Kalman, Matthew (8 May 2007). [http://www.boston.com/news/world/middleeast/articles/2007/05/08/herods_tomb_reportedly_found_inside_his_desert_palace/ \"Herod's tomb reportedly found inside his desert palace\"] ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', Accessed 7 May 2013.</ref> The site is located at the exact location given by Josephus, atop tunnels and water pools, at a flattened desert site, halfway up the hill to [[Herodium]], 12 kilometers (7.5&nbsp;mi) south of Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite news| title=Archaeologists Find Tomb of King Herod |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/science/2007-05-07-3709859735_x.htm  |first=Steve |last=Weizman |newspaper=USA Today |date= 8 May 2007 |agency= Associated Press|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref> The tomb contained a broken [[sarcophagus]] but no remains of a body.\n\nThe [[Israel Nature and Parks Authority]] and the [[Gush Etzion Regional Council]] intend to recreate the tomb out of a light plastic material.<ref>Hasson, Nir (29 January 2012). [http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/top-archaeologists-condemn-israeli-plan-to-rebuild-ancient-tomb-1.409779?localLinksEnabled=false \"Top archaeologists condemn Israeli plan to rebuild ancient tomb\"], ''Haaretz''. Accessed 8 May 2013.</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, archaeologists Joseph Patrich and Benjamin Arubas challenged the identification of the tomb as that of Herod. According to Patrich and Arubas, the tomb is too modest to be Herod's and has several unlikely features. Roi Porat, who replaced Netzer as excavation leader after the latter's death, stood by the identification.<ref name=Hasson2013>{{cite news | newspaper = Haaretz | title = Archaeological stunner: Not Herod's Tomb after all? | author = Nir Hasson | date = October 11, 2013 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/jewish/archaeology/.premium-1.551881 }}</ref>\n\n==Opinion of his reign==\n[[Macrobius]] (c. 400 CE), one of the last pagan writers in Rome, in his book ''[[Saturnalia (Macrobius)|Saturnalia]]'', wrote: \u201cWhen it was heard that, as part of the slaughter of boys up to two years old, Herod, king of the Jews, had ordered his own son to be killed, he [the Emperor Augustus] remarked, \u2018It is better to be Herod\u2019s pig [Gr. hys] than his son\u2019 [Gr. huios]\u201d. This was a reference of how Herod, as a Jew, would not kill pigs, but had three of his sons, and many others, killed.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Birth of the Messiah|last = Brown|first = Raymond|publisher = Doubleday|year = 1993|location = New York}}</ref>\n\nAccording to contemporary historians, Herod the Great \"is perhaps the only figure in ancient Jewish history who has been loathed equally by Jewish and Christian posterity\",<ref name=\"Schwartz 59-62\"/> depicted both from Jews and Christians as a tyrant and bloodthirsty ruler.<ref name=\"Schwartz 59-62\"/> The study of Herod's reign includes polarizing opinions on the man himself. Modern critics have described him as \"the evil genius of the Judean nation\",<ref>Tierney, John. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/07289c.htm \"Herod: Herod the Great\"], ''Catholic Encyclopedia'' (1910): \"Herod, surnamed the Great, called by [[Heinrich Graetz|Gr\u00e4tz]] \"the evil genius of the Judean nation\" [https://archive.org/stream/historyofje02grae#page/76/mode/2up (''Hist''., v. II, p. 77)].</ref> and as one who would be \"prepared to commit any crime in order to gratify his unbounded ambition.\"<ref>[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=630&letter=H&search=herod Herod&nbsp;I] at ''Jewish Encyclopedia'': \"above all, he was prepared to commit any crime in order to gratify his unbounded ambition\".</ref> His extraordinary spending spree is cited as one of the causes of the serious impoverishment of the people he ruled, adding to the opinion that his reign was exclusively negative.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Shaye|title=Ancient Israel: From Abraham to the Roman Destruction of the Temple|publisher=Prentice Hall Biblical Archeological Society|pages=273}}</ref> \nHerod's religious policies gained a mixed response from the Jewish populace. Although Herod considered himself king of the Jews, he let it be known that he also represented the non-Jews living in Judea, building temples for other religions outside of the Jewish areas of his kingdom. Many Jews questioned the authenticity of Herod's Judaism on account of his [[Idumean]] background and his infamous murders of members of his family. However, he generally respected traditional Jewish observances in his public life. For instance, he minted coins without human images to be used in Jewish areas and acknowledged the sanctity of the [[Second Temple]] by employing priests in the construction of the Temple.<ref name=\"SCohen272\">Cohen, Shaye. \"Roman Domination: The Jewish Revolt and the Destruction of the Second Temple,\" in ''Ancient Israel'', ed. Hershel Shanks. (Biblical Archaeology Society, 1999), p. 272.</ref>\n\nAlong with holding some respect for the Jewish culture in his public life, there is also evidence of Herod's sensitivity towards Jewish traditions in his private life with the presence of around 40 ritual baths or ''mikvehs'' found in several of his palaces.<ref>Eyal Regev, \"Herod's Jewish Ideology Facing Romanization: On Intermarriage, Ritual Baths, and Speeches,\" ''The Jewish Quarterly Review'' 100 (2010): 210.</ref> These ''mikvehs'' were known for being used in [[Tumah and taharah|Jewish purity rituals]] during this time where Jewish people could submerge themselves in these pools and purify their bodies without the presence of a priest.<ref>Regev, \"Herod's Jewish Ideology,\" 207.</ref> There is some speculation as to whether or not these baths were actual ''mikvehs'' as they have also been identified as stepped ''frigidarium'' or Roman cold-water baths; however, several historians have identified these baths as a combination of both types.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Regev, \"Herod's Jewish Ideology,\" 211.</ref> While it has been proven that Herod showed a great amount of disrespect towards the Jewish religion, scholar Eyal Regev suggests that the presence of these ritual baths shows that Herod found ritual purity important enough in his private life to place a large number of these baths in his palaces despite his several connections to gentiles and pagan cults.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> These baths also show, Regev continues, that the combination of the Roman ''frigidarium'' and the Jewish ''mikvehs'' suggests that Herod sought for there to be some type of combination between the Roman and Jewish cultures as he enjoyed the purity of Jewish tradition and the comfort of Roman luxury simultaneously.<ref>Regev, \"Herod's Jewish Ideology,\" 212.</ref>\n\nHowever, he was also praised for his work, being considered the greatest builder in Jewish history,{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} and one who \"knew his place and followed [the] rules.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Shaye|title=Ancient Israel: From Abraham to the Roman Destruction of the Temple|publisher=Prentice Hall Biblical Archeological Society|pages=270}}</ref> In fact, what is left of his building ventures are now popular tourist attractions in the Middle East, which many have come to cherish as both a historical and religious area.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Shaye|title=Ancient Israel: From Abraham to the Roman Destruction of the Temple|publisher=Prentice Hall Biblical Archeological Society|pages=296}}</ref>\n\n==Chronology==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=May 2017}}\n{{further|Herodian kingdom}}\n\n===30s BC===\n* 39\u201337 BC \u2013 Roman war against [[Antigonus the Hasmonean|Antigonus]]. After the conquest of Jerusalem and victory over Antigonus, [[Mark Antony]] executes him.\n* 36 BC \u2013 Herod makes his 17-year-old brother-in-law, [[Aristobulus III]], high priest, fearing that the Jews would appoint Aristobulus&nbsp;III as \"King of the Jews\" in his place.\n* 35 BC \u2013 Aristobulus III is drowned at a party on Herod's orders.\n* 32 BC \u2013 The war against [[Nabataean kingdom|Nabatea begins]], with victory one year later.\n* 31 BC \u2013 Judea suffers a devastating [[earthquake]]. [[Augustus|Octavian]] defeats Mark Antony, so Herod switches allegiance to Octavian, later known as Augustus.\n* 30 BC \u2013 Herod is shown great favor by Octavian, who at [[Rhodes]] confirms him as King of Judea.\n\n===20s BC===\n* 29 BC \u2013 [[Josephus]] writes that Herod had great passion and also great jealousy concerning his wife, [[Mariamne I]]. She learns of Herod's plans to murder her, and stops sleeping with him. Herod puts her on trial on a charge of [[adultery]]. His sister, [[Salome I]], was chief witness against her. Mariamne I's mother Alexandra made an appearance and incriminated her own daughter. Historians say her mother was next on Herod's list to be executed and did this only to save her own life. Mariamne was executed, and Alexandra declared herself Queen, stating that Herod was mentally unfit to serve. Josephus wrote that this was Alexandra's strategic mistake; Herod executed her without trial.\n* 28 BC \u2013 Herod executed his brother-in-law Kostobar<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 15.7.8</ref> (husband of Salome, father to [[Berenice (daughter of Salome)|Berenice]]) for conspiracy. Large festival in Jerusalem, as Herod had built a theatre and an [[amphitheatre]].\n* 27 BC \u2013 An assassination attempt on Herod was foiled. To honor Augustus, Herod rebuilt [[Samaria]] and renamed it Sebaste.\n* 25 BC \u2013 Herod imported grain from [[Egypt]] and started an aid program to combat the widespread hunger and disease that followed a massive [[drought]]. He also waives a third of the taxes. Herod began construction on [[Caesarea Maritima]] and its harbor.\n* 23 BC\u2013 Herod built a palace in Jerusalem and the fortress Herodion (Herodium) in Judea. He married his third wife, [[Mariamne (third wife of Herod)|Mariamne II]], the daughter of the priest Simon Boethus; immediately Herodes deprived [[Jesus, son of Fabus|Jesus the son of Phabet]] of the high priesthood and conferred that dignity on Simon.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 15.9.3</ref>\n* 22 BC \u2013 The Roman emperor Augustus granted him the regions Trachonitis, Batanaea, and Auranitis to the northeast.\n* Circa 20 BC \u2013 Expansion started on the [[Temple Mount]]; Herod completely rebuilt the [[Second Temple of Jerusalem]].\n\n===10s BC===\n* Circa 18 BC \u2013 Herod traveled for the second time to Rome.\n* 14 BC \u2013 Herod supported the Jews in [[Anatolia]] and [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]]. Owing to the prosperity in Judaea he waived a quarter of the taxes.\n* 13 BC \u2013 Herod made his first-born son Antipater (his son by Doris) first heir in his [[will (law)|will]].\n* 12 BC \u2013 Herod suspected his sons from his marriage to Mariamne I, Alexander and Aristobulus, of threatening his life. He took them to [[Aquileia]] to be tried. Augustus reconciled the three. Herod supported the financially strapped [[Olympic Games]] and ensured their future. Herod amended his will so that Alexander and Aristobulus rose in the royal succession, but Antipater would be higher in the succession.\n* Circa 10 BC \u2013 The newly expanded temple in Jerusalem was inaugurated. War against the Nabateans began.\n\n===First decade BCE===\n[[File:Herod IMG 0594.JPG|thumb|Tomb of Herod]]\n\n* 9 BC \u2013 [[Caesarea Maritima]] was inaugurated. Owing to the course of the war against the Nabateans, Herod fell into disgrace with Augustus. Herod again suspected Alexander of plotting to kill him.\n* 8 BC \u2013 Herod accused his sons Alexander and Aristobulus of [[treason|high treason]]. Herod reconciled with Augustus, who also gave him the permission to proceed legally against his sons.\n* 7 BC\u2013 The court hearing took place in Berytos ([[Beirut]]) before a Roman court. His sons Alexander and Aristobulus were found guilty and executed. The succession changed so that Antipater was the exclusive successor to the throne. In second place the succession incorporated (Herod) Philip, his son by Mariamne&nbsp;II.\n* 6 BC \u2013 Herod proceeded against the [[Pharisee]]s.\n* 5 BC \u2013 Antipater was brought before the court charged with the intended murder of Herod. Herod, by now seriously ill, named his son (Herod) Antipas (from his fourth marriage with [[Malthace]]) as his successor.\n* 4 BC \u2013 Young disciples smashed the golden eagle over the main entrance of the Temple of Jerusalem after the Pharisee teachers claimed it was an idolatrous Roman symbol. Herod arrested them, brought them to court, and sentenced them. Augustus approved the [[death penalty]] for Antipater. Herod then executed his son, and again changed his will: [[Herod Archelaus|Archelaus]] (from the marriage with Malthace) would rule as ethnarch over the [[Tetrarchy (Judea)|tetrachy of Judea]], while [[Herod Antipas|Antipas]] (by Malthace) and [[Herod Philip II|Philip]] (from the fifth marriage with Cleopatra of Jerusalem) would rule as tetrarchs over Galilee and [[Perea (Holy Land)|Peraea]] (Transjordan), also over Gaulanitis ([[Golan]]), [[Trachonitis]] (Hebrew: Argob), Batanaea (now Ard-el-Bathanyeh) and [[Panias]]. [[Salome I]] was also given a small [[toparchy]] in the Gaza region. As Augustus did not confirm his will, no one received the title of King; however, the three sons were granted rule of the stated territories.\n\n==Wives and children==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Herod's wives and children'''\n! Wife\n! Children\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| Doris\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son [[Antipater (son of Herod the Great)|Antipater II]], executed 4&nbsp;BC\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| [[Mariamne I]], daughter of Hasmonean [[Alexander of Judaea|Alexandros]] and [[Alexandra the Maccabee]],<br> executed 29 BC\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son [[Alexander, son of Herod|Alexander]], executed 7&nbsp;BCE\n* son [[Aristobulus IV]], executed 7&nbsp;BCE\n* daughter [[Salampsio]]\n* daughter Cypros\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| [[Mariamne (third wife of Herod)|Mariamne II]], daughter of [[Kohen Gadol|High-Priest]] [[Simon son of Boethus|Simon]]'''\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son [[Herod II]]\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| [[Malthace]]\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son [[Herod Archelaus]] - ethnarch\n* son [[Herod Antipas]] - tetrarch\n* daughter [[Olympias (Herodian)|Olympias]]\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| [[Cleopatra of Jerusalem]]\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son [[Philip the Tetrarch]] - tetrarch\n* son Herod\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| Pallas\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* son Phasael\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| Phaidra\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* daughter Roxanne\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| Elpis\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* daughter [[Salome (daughter of Herod the Great)|Salome]]\n|-\n| a cousin (name unknown)\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* no known children\n|-\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"| a niece (name unknown)\n|style=\"vertical-align: top\"|\n* no known children\n|}\nIt is very probable that Herod had more children, especially with the last wives, and also that he had more daughters, as female births at that time were often not recorded.<ref>Josephus, ''Antiquities'', 18.1.2\u20133.</ref>\n\n==Family trees==\n\n===Ancestors===\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | Ant |y| Cyp | | Ant=[[Antipater the Idumaean|Antipater<br>the Idumaean]]|Cyp=[[Cypros]]<br>([[Nabataean kingdom|Nabatean]])}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | }}\n{{tree chart | |,|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{tree chart | Pha | | Her | | Jos | | Phe | | Sal  |Pha=[[Phasael]]|Her='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Jos=Joseph|Phe=Pheroras|Sal=[[Salome I]]| }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | | | | | Ari |~| Ber |Ari=[[Aristobulus IV]]|Ber=[[Berenice (daughter of Salome)|Berenice]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n===Marriages and descendants===\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | HeG |y| Wif | | HeG='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Wif=Doris}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | Ant  | | | | |Ant=[[Antipater (son of Herod the Great)|Antipater II]]<br>d. 4 BCE}}\n{{tree chart/end}}{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | | | | | | }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | Hus |y| Wif | |Hus=[[Alexander of Judaea|Alexander]]|Wif=[[Alexandra the Maccabee|Alexandra]]}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | |,|-|^|-|.| }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | Hus |y| Wif | | Ar3 |Ar3=[[Aristobulus III of Judea|Aristobulus III]]<br>d. 35 BCE|Hus='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Wif=[[Mariamne I]]<br>d. 29 BCE}}\n{{tree chart | |,|-|-|-|-|-|^|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{tree chart | Ar4 |y| Ber | | Ale | | Ph2 |~| Sal | | Ant |~| Cyp |Ar4=[[Aristobulus IV|Aristobulus]]<br>d. 7 BCE|Ber=[[Berenice (daughter of Salome)|Berenice]]|Ale=[[Alexander, son of Herod|Alexander]]<br>d. 7 BCE|Sal=[[Salampsio]]|Ph2=Phasael II|Cyp=Cypros II<sup>\u2020</sup>|Ant=Antipater<sup>\u2020</sup>}}\n{{tree chart | |,|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{tree chart | Ma3 |~| HAs | | He5 | | Her |~| He2 | | HAa | | ArM |Ma3=[[Mariamne III]]|HAs=[[Herod Archelaus]]|He5=[[Herod of Chalcis|Herod V]]|Her=[[Herodias]]|He2=1. [[Herod II]] {{dubious|NOT! Son of Herod the Great & Mariamne. Who was meant here?|date=December 2015}}<br>2. [[Herod Antipas]]|HAa=[[Herod Agrippa|Herod Agrippa I]]|ArM=[[Aristobulus Minor]]}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|v|-|^|-|.| }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | | | HA2 | | BdA | | MdA | | DdA ||HA2=[[Herod Agrippa II]]|BdA=[[Berenice (daughter of Herod Agrippa)|Berenice]]|MdA=[[Mariamne (daughter of Herod Agrippa)|Mariamne]]|DdA=[[Drusilla (daughter of Herod Agrippa)|Drusilla]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | SsB | | |SsB=[[Simon son of Boethus|Simon Boethus]]<br>([[High Priest of Israel|High Priest]])}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | HeG |y| Wif | | | | | | |HeG='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Wif=[[Mariamne (third wife of Herod)|Mariamne II]]}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | He2 | | | | |He2=[[Herod II]]}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | HeG |y| Wif | | |HeG='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Wif=[[Malthace]]<br>(Samaritan)}}\n{{tree chart | Ar4 | | | | |!| | | | | | |Ar4=[[Aretas IV Philopatris|Aretas IV]]<br>king of Arabia|}}\n{{tree chart | |!| | | |,|-|^|-|-|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|.| | }}\n{{tree chart | Phs |~| HAn | | Ma3 |~| HAr | | Oly |Phs=Phasaelis|HAn=[[Herod Antipas]]|Ma3=[[Mariamne III]]|HAr=[[Herod Archelaus]]|Oly=[[Olympias (Herodian)|Olympias]]| }}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n\n{{tree chart/start}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | HeG |y| Wif | | | | | | |HeG='''Herod<br>the Great'''|Wif=[[Cleopatra of Jerusalem|Cleopatra<br>of Jerusalem]]}}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | }}\n{{tree chart | | | | | | | PtT | | | | |PtT=[[Philip the Tetrarch]]<br>d. 34 CE}}\n{{tree chart/end}}\n\n; Notes.\n:\u2020 {{cite book|title=Calmets Great dictionary of the holy bible|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hc03AQAAMAAJ&pg=PT340|year=1812|page=340|chapter=Cypros II|quote=Image of [https://books.google.com/books?id=Hc03AQAAMAAJ&pg=PT340&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U2fnb6sbHNDOyiGDDq4z9k2eoHs6A&ci=483%2C822%2C407%2C274&edge=0 p.&nbsp;340] at [[Google Books]]}}\n:\u2021 [http://www.swartzentrover.com/cotor/Bible/Bible/NT/Gospel%20&%20Acts/Herod%20FamilyTree.htm Family Tree of Herod]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cultural depictions of Herod the Great]]\n* [[Herodian dynasty]]\n* [[Herodian kingdom]]\n* [[Herod's Palace (Jerusalem)|Herod's Palace]]\n* [[Judean date palm#Germination of 2000-year-old seed|Judean date palm: Germination of 2000-year-old seed]]\n* [[List of biblical figures identified in extra-biblical sources]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==<!--references to any of these would improve this article-->\n* {{cite journal|last=Brandon|first=S.&nbsp;G.&nbsp;F.|title=Herod the Great: Judaea's Most Able but Most Hated King|journal=History Today|year=1962|volume=12|pages=234\u2013242}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Grant (author)|title=Herod the Great|year=1971|publisher=American Heritage Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-07-024073-5|url=https://archive.org/details/herodgreat00gran_0}}\n* G\u00fcnther, Linda-Marie (hg.) ''Herodes und Jerusalem'' (Stuttgart: Franz Steiner Verlag, 2009).\n* G\u00fcnther, Linda-Marie (hg.) ''Herodes und Rom'' (Stuttgart: Franz Steiner Verlag, 2007).\n* Jacobson, David M. and Nikos Kokkinos (eds). ''Herod and Augustus: Papers Held at the Institute of Jewish Studies Conference, University College London, 21\u201323 June 2005'' (Leiden, Brill, 2009) (IJS Studies in Judaica, 6).\n* [[Aryeh Kasher|Kasher, Aryeh]] and Witztum, Eliezer. ''King Herod: A Persecuted Persecutor