egory:1st-century BC Herodian rulers]]\n[[Category:Biblical murderers]]\n[[Category:Herodian dynasty]]\n[[Category:Ancient history of Jordan]]\n[[Category:History of Palestine (region)]]\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Masada]]\n[[Category:Roman client rulers]]\n[[Category:New Testament people]]\n", "name_user": "Fauld", "label": "safe", "comment": "Consistency for historical reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_the_Great"}
{"title_page": "El Tucuche", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name           = El Tucuche\n| photo          = El Tucuche 45.jpg\n| photo_caption  = El gobler\n| photo_size     = \n| elevation_m    = 4000\n| elevation_ref  = \n| prominence_m   = 526\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"mapcarta\">[http://mapcarta.com/19493740 Northern Range Reserve]</ref>\n| map            = Trinidad and tobago\n| map_caption    = \n| map_size       = 300\n| location = Maracas Valley, [[Tunapuna\u2013Piarco]], [[Trinidad]]\n| state = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| label_position = bottom\n| listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]]\n| range = [[Northern Range]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|10|44|00|N|61|25|00|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''El Tucuche''' (937 m) is the second highest peak in [[Trinidad]]'s [[Northern Range]] and is noted for its interesting pyramidal shape. It is fabled in [[Amerindian]] lore as a sacred mountain. There are Amerindian petroglyphs on a rock outcrop below the mountain. These are the only petroglyphs found in the country.\n\nIts summit is home to the golden tree frog (''[[Phytotriades auratus]]''). On the summit of El Tucuche, [[elfin woodland]] can be found.{{fact|date=October 2017}} The vegetation is usually gnarled and short, due to the high elevation, exposure to clouds and prevailing winds. At the foot of the mountain lies the village of Lluengo, home to approximately 2,000 residents.\n\nWildlife on El Tucuche includes animals such as the El Tucuche Golden Tree Frog (''[[Phytotriades auratus]]''), the [[Red Brocket Deer]], the Fer-de-lance (''[[Bothrops atrox]]''), the [[Bearded Bellbird]], the [[Orange-winged Amazon]] Parrot, the [[White-bearded Manakin]], the Trinidad Stream Frog (''[[Mannophryne trinitatis]]'') and the Emperor Morpho Butterfly (''[[Morpho peleides]]'') to name just a few. Notable vegetation on the higher slopes includes mosses, tree-ferns and bromeliads (including ''[[Glomeropitcairnia erectiflora]]'' - the microhabitat of the El Tucuche Golden Tree Frog); and ''[[Heliconia]]''s on the lower to middle slopes. Old abandoned [[Theobroma cacao|Cocoa]] estates that are reverting to forest occur in some areas of the lower slopes. The nation's highest waterfall, Maracas falls, lies at the foothills of El Tucuche, and is 91.5 meters (300 feet) high.{{fact|date=October 2017}}\n\nEl Tucuche is often climbed by hikers.{{fact|date=October 2017}} There are two summits, the first summit ascends to above 2,000 feet (800 meters) and displays a 1000 feet sheer-vertical cliff. The second and highest summit is at over 3,000 feet (936 meters) and is pyramid-shaped. When clouds aren't present, the nation's capital, [[Port Of Spain]], the [[Caroni Swamp]] and [[Central Range, Trinidad and Tobago|Main Ridge]] can be viewed from the summit. The mountain also has views of [[Maracas Beach]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Trinidad (island)]]\n\n\n{{Trinidad-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name           = El Tucuche\n| photo          = El Tucuche 45.jpg\n| photo_caption  = El Tucuche\n| photo_size     = \n| elevation_m    = 936\n| elevation_ref  = \n| prominence_m   = 526\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"mapcarta\">[http://mapcarta.com/19493740 Northern Range Reserve]</ref>\n| map            = Trinidad and Tobago\n| map_caption    = \n| map_size       = 300\n| location = Maracas Valley, [[Tunapuna\u2013Piarco]], [[Trinidad]]\n| state = [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n| label_position = bottom\n| listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]]\n| range = [[Northern Range]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|10|44|00|N|61|25|00|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''El Tucuche''' (936 m) is the second highest peak in [[Trinidad]]'s [[Northern Range]] and is noted for its interesting pyramidal shape. It is fabled in [[Amerindian]] lore as a sacred mountain. There are Amerindian petroglyphs on a rock outcrop below the mountain. These are the only petroglyphs found in the country.\n\nIts summit is home to the golden tree frog (''[[Phytotriades auratus]]''). On the summit of El Tucuche, [[elfin woodland]] can be found.{{fact|date=October 2017}} The vegetation is usually gnarled and short, due to the high elevation, exposure to clouds and prevailing winds. At the foot of the mountain lies the village of Lluengo, home to approximately 2,000 residents.\n\nWildlife on El Tucuche includes animals such as the El Tucuche Golden Tree Frog (''[[Phytotriades auratus]]''), the [[Red Brocket Deer]], the Fer-de-lance (''[[Bothrops atrox]]''), the [[Bearded Bellbird]], the [[Orange-winged Amazon]] Parrot, the [[White-bearded Manakin]], the Trinidad Stream Frog (''[[Mannophryne trinitatis]]'') and the Emperor Morpho Butterfly (''[[Morpho peleides]]'') to name just a few. Notable vegetation on the higher slopes includes mosses, tree-ferns and bromeliads (including ''[[Glomeropitcairnia erectiflora]]'' - the microhabitat of the El Tucuche Golden Tree Frog); and ''[[Heliconia]]''s on the lower to middle slopes. Old abandoned [[Theobroma cacao|Cocoa]] estates that are reverting to forest occur in some areas of the lower slopes. The nation's highest waterfall, Maracas falls, lies at the foothills of El Tucuche, and is 91.5 meters (300 feet) high.{{fact|date=October 2017}}\n\nEl Tucuche is often climbed by hikers.{{fact|date=October 2017}} There are two summits, the first summit ascends to above 2,000 feet (800 meters) and displays a 1000 feet sheer-vertical cliff. The second and highest summit is at over 3,000 feet (936 meters) and is pyramid-shaped. When clouds aren't present, the nation's capital, [[Port Of Spain]], the [[Caroni Swamp]] and [[Central Range, Trinidad and Tobago|Main Ridge]] can be viewed from the summit. The mountain also has views of [[Maracas Beach]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Trinidad (island)]]\n\n\n{{Trinidad-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2803:1500:1200:911d:b847:5b5f:b493:a6ee", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Tucuche"}
{"title_page": "Visions of a Life", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Visions of a Life\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Wolf Alice]]\n| cover      = Wolf Alice - Visions of a Life.png\n| released   = {{Start date|2017|9|29|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[indie pop]]|[[dream pop]]|[[psychedelic rock]]|[[shoegazing]]|[[post-punk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=46|s=39}}\n| label      = [[Dirty Hit]]\n| producer   = [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]\n| prev_title = [[My Love Is Cool]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| type        = studio\n| name        = Visions of a Life\n| single1     = [[Yuk Foo]]\n| single1date = 12 June 2017\n| single2     = [[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\n| single2date = 5 July 2017\n| single3     = [[Beautifully Unconventional]]\n| single3date = 14 August 2017\n| single4     = [[Heavenward]]\n| single4date = 18 September 2017\n| single5     = Formidable Cool\n| single5date = 16 February 2018\n| single6     = [[Sadboy]]\n| single6date = 2 March 2018\n| single7     = [[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\n| single7date = 8 May 2018\n}}\n}}\n'''''Visions of a Life''''' is the second studio album by English [[alternative rock]] band [[Wolf Alice]], released on 29 September 2017 through [[Dirty Hit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2017/06/12/wolf-alice-yuk-foo-new-album-visions-of-a-life-2017-listen|title=Wolf Alice return! Hear 'Yuk Foo' from new album 'Vision of a Life'|work=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |last=Richards |first=Will |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The album received acclaim from music critics and appeared on several year-end lists, as well as winning the 2018 [[Mercury Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mercuryprize.com/news/see-the-2018-shortlist |title=See the 2018 Shortlist |work=[[Mercury Prize]] |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nIn November 2016, drummer Joel Amey said the band is \"very much in the middle of writing some new music.\" In May 2017, the band teased the album by sending mysterious postcards with song titles and lyrics of each of the album tracks to fans on their mailing list, which they later posted on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-sending-mysterious-postcards-fans-2078205|title=Wolf Alice are sending mysterious postcards to fans|work=[[NME]] |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> On 12 June, the band premiered the lead single \"[[Yuk Foo]]\" on [[BBC Radio 1]],<ref name=\"NME1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-announce-new-single-album-and-uk-and-world-tour-2087538|title=Wolf Alice announce new single 'Yuk Foo', second album and UK and world tour|work=NME |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> with a lyric video being later uploaded to the band's [[Vevo]] channel on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eM75EQlDVLA|title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Yuk Foo (Lyric Video)|website=[[YouTube]] |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> They announced the release date of their upcoming album ''Visions of a Life'' would be on 29 September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/wolf-alice-announce-sophomore-album-visions-of-a-life-share-single-yuk-foo-listen|title=Wolf Alice announce sophomore album, Visions of a Life, share \"Yuk Foo\" \u2014 listen|work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |last=Kaye |first=Ben |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The band stated that the album is \"pretty varied\" and that they wanted to \"come out with a big bang,\" which is why they chose \"Yuk Foo\" as the first track to be released, adding that the rest of the album is \"pretty different to that.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BBCR1|number=874351394735697920|date=12 June 2017|title=\"We wanted to come out with a big bang\" @WolfAliceMusic are @AnnieMac's #HottestRecord with 'Yuk Foo' & tour news |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The band announced a world tour in support of the album with the dates being posted to the band's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wolfalice.co.uk|title=Wolf Alice|website=wolfalice.co.uk |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The tour includes their biggest headline show to date at [[Alexandra Palace]] in [[London]] on 24 November.<ref name=\"NME1\" /> The album was produced by [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]].<ref name=\"NME1\"/>\n\nOn 5 July, the band released the second single, \"[[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\", and made the album available for pre-order, along with the reveal of the album cover, which features a photo of lead vocalist Ellie Rowsell's aunt, Hellen, \"playing the classic game of 'dance round the horse's skull in your Sunday best'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-dont-delete-the-kisses-2098502|title=Wolf Alice release new single 'Don't Delete The Kisses' and share 'Visions Of A Life' album artwork|work=NME |last=Morgan Britton |first=Luke |date=5 July 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=wolfalicemusic|number=882647191499796480|date=5 July 2017|title=That's a photo of Ellie's aunty Helen playing the classic game of 'dance round the horse's skull in your Sunday best' |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The accompanying music video for \"Don't Delete the Kisses\" was released on 11 August.<ref name=\"Video\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WqxE-zppu30 |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Don't Delete the Kisses |website=[[YouTube]] |author=WolfAliceVEVO |date=11 August 2017 |accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> The third single, \"[[Beautifully Unconventional]]\", was premiered on [[Annie Mac]]'s BBC Radio 1 show on 14 August, and was subsequently released for digital download and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/listen-wolf-alice-new-track-beautifully-unconventional-2124540 |title=Listen to Wolf Alice's new track, 'Beautifully Unconventional' |work=NME |date=14 August 2017 |first=Will |last=Butler |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> A 1950s-inspired music video was released on 11 September.<ref>{{cite web |last=Myers |first=Owen |url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/09/11/wolf-alice-beautifully-unconventional-video-premiere |title=Wolf Alice Get A Glamorous '50s Makeover in Their \"Beautifully Unconventional\" Video |work=[[The Fader]] |date=11 September 2017 |accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> The band released \"[[Heavenward]]\" as the fourth single on 18 September. The song premiered on [[Zane Lowe]]'s Beats 1 radio show, and subsequently released for digital download and streaming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://diymag.com/2017/09/18/wolf-alice-heavenward-album-visions-of-a-life |title=Wolf Alice unveil 'Heavenward' from forthcoming album, 'Visions of a Life' |work=DIY |date=18 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> According to a press release, the song is about the death of a friend.<ref>{{cite web |last=Morgan Britton |first=Luke |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-heavenward-2142334 |title=Stream Wolf Alice's personal new single 'Heavenward' |work=NME |date=18 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> The album's fifth single, \"Formidable Cool\", was released on 16 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/formidable-cool-edit-single/1345743393 |title=Formidable Cool (Edit) \u2013 Single by Wolf Alice |work=[[iTunes Store]] (UK) |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> and was serviced to UK [[contemporary hit radio]] on 9 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist |title=BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Playlist |publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]] |accessdate=23 March 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310143326/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist |archivedate=10 March 2018}}</ref> On 2 March 2018, \"[[Sadboy]]\" was released as the sixth single, followed by an accompanying music video three days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/sadboy-edit-single/1349917959 |title=Sadboy (Edit) \u2013 Single by Wolf Alice |work=iTunes Store (Canada) |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=WolfAliceVEVO |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6sRAzBWCnfM |title=Wolf Alice - Sadboy |work=[[YouTube]] |date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> \"[[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\" was released on 8 May 2018 as the seventh single.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Space & Time / Formiddable Cool |type=LP liner notes |others=Wolf Alice |publisher=[[Dirty Hit]] |year=2018 |id=DH00317}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on 30 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-wolf-alices-ellie-rowsell-become-runaway-bride-epic-space-time-video-2328628 |title=Watch Wolf Alice\u2019s Ellie Rowsell become runaway bride in epic 'Space and Time' video |work=NME |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n''Visions of a Life'' is primarily an [[alternative rock]]<ref name=\"Skinny\"/> and [[noise rock]] album,<ref name=\"RS\"/> and was noted by numerous critics to take influences from various genres, including [[shoegazing|shoegaze]], [[punk rock]], [[dream pop]], [[grunge]], [[psychedelic music|psychedelia]], [[contemporary folk music|folk]], [[space rock]], [[synth-pop]], [[hardcore punk|hardcore]] and [[electronica]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pearson |first=Rick |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/music/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-review-a3647286.html |title=Wolf Alice - Visions of a Life, review |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=29 September 2017 |accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"P4K\"/><ref name=\"IrishTimes\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.0/10<ref>{{cite web |title=Visions Of A Life by Wolf Alice reviews |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8941/Wolf-Alice-Visions-Of-A-Life.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 81/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |title=Reviews and Tracks for Visions of a Life by Wolf Alice |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/visions-of-a-life/wolf-alice |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |last=Phares |first=Heather |title=Visions of a Life \u2013 Wolf Alice |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/visions-of-a-life-mw0003076565 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = B+<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite web |last=Ihnat |first=Gwen |title=Wolf Alice's Visions Of A Life finds beauty in chaos |url=https://www.avclub.com/wolf-alice-s-visions-of-a-life-finds-beauty-in-chaos-1818840781 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web |last=Mumford |first=Gwilym |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life review \u2013 exuberant guitar-driven genre jumble |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/28/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-review |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite web |last=Clayton-Lea |first=Tony |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life album review: Londoners enter new chapter |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/album-reviews/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-album-review-londoners-enter-new-chapter-1.3230724 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cameron |first=Keith |title=Ahead of the pack |work=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |issue=288 |date=November 2017 |page=92}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last=Daly |first=Rhian |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 'Visions Of A Life' Album Review |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/wolf-alice-visions-life-review-2145110 |website=NME |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 7.0/10<ref name=\"P4K\">{{cite web |last=Monroe |first=Jazz |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life/ |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 October 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Barton |first=Laura |title=Howling Success |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=378 |date=November 2017 |page=110}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web |last=Levy |first=Joe |title=Review: Wolf Alice Deliver Noise-Rock Seduction on Second LP |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-wolf-alices-visions-of-a-life-w506994 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=4 October 2017 |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10score = 6/10<ref>{{cite journal |last=Richards |first=Sam |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=246 |date=November 2017 |page=39}}</ref>\n}}\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 81, based on 21 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\"/> Rhian Daly of ''[[NME]]'' called it the album of the year and claimed that \"with ''Visions of a Life'' Wolf Alice are removing any doubt about their status in the UK music scene. Best band in Britain? 100 per cent.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/> ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''{{'}}s Luke Beardsworth called the album \"a phenomenal achievement. It has captured on record the thrill, angst, sadness and uncertainty of being in your twenties and not really knowing what's going to happen or should happen. All of it is never anything less than intoxicating, heartfelt and effortless ... It feels like one of the most crucial, relevant, angry, cool and vibrant records of the decade. Wolf Alice, as fantastic bands tend to, have completely disregarded the idea that a second album should be difficult and turned out a genuine masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite web |last=Beardsworth |first=Luke |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/20085/reviews/4151372 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=26 September 2017 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s Heather Phares described the album as \"a reflection of a young band trying out all its possibilities,\" and thought it's \"more scattered than ''[[My Love Is Cool]]'', but its best songs hint at even more potential.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> ''[[The A.V. Club]]''{{'}}s Gwen Ihnat said \"In lesser hands, this kind of sonic disparity could be chaotic and confusing\u2014but with Rowsell's voice as the guiding light, ''Visions'' is a captivating, enjoyable ride.\"<ref name=\"AVClub\"/> Will Richards of ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' said, \"there's no difficult second album syndrome here. ''Visions of a Life'' is a gorgeously twisted beast that keeps Wolf Alice on the path to being Britain's best band.\"<ref name=\"DIY\">{{cite web |last=Richards |first=Will |url=http://diymag.com/2017/09/28/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-album-review |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |work=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nMatt the Raven from ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]'' stated that the album \"may be a somewhat inconsistent journey but it's also pure rock and roll splendor from a band that's super talented and not afraid to take chances.\"<ref name=\"UTR\">{{cite web |last=the Raven |first=Matt |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/reviews/wolf_alice_visions_of_a_life |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life Review |work=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>  ''[[Kerrang!]]'' stated that \"the eclectic sounds of Wolf Alice's debut made them stars, but this sequel finds them doing everything bigger and better.\"<ref name=\"MC\"/> Bella Spencer of ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]'' wrote, \"the album caters for all \u2013 there are heavy tracks for hardcore fans and songs with a more approachable indie feel for those who need a gentle introduction to the ways of the Wolf. So sit back, relax and scream to your heart's content.\"<ref name=\"Skinny\">{{cite web |last=Spencer |first=Bella |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life album review |url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |website=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] |date=25 September 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> In a more mixed review, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s Geoff Nelson thought that \"''Visions of a Life'' is often full, seeming to overflow. But the substance is lacking, resulting in a tiring trip through a band gamely trying not to merely cover itself.\"<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Geoff |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/album-review-wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |website=Consequence of Sound |date=22 September 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> In his rave review for ''[[musicOMH]]'', critic Craig Jones stated that \"there are no low points in this relentless record. At times it is beastly, baring its teeth. At others, it's divinely angelic\", continuing: \"So relevant and of its moment, touching on the little things which make up our lives then showing utter disdain to the establishment, you'll struggle to find many better albums than ''Visions of a Life'' this year.\"<ref name=\"MusicOMH\">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Craig |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |work=[[musicOMH]] |date=5 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| Favourite Albums of 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|1}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4151506-drowned-in-sounds-favourite-albums-of-2017|title=Drowned in Sound's Favourite Albums of 2017|work= [[Drowned in Sound]] |date=22 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''RIOT Mag''\n| RIOT's Albums Of The Year 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|6}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riotmag.co/riots-albums-year-2017-top-10|title=RIOT's Albums Of The Year 2017|work=RIOT Mag|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| Albums of the Year\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|2}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/nmes-albums-of-the-year-2017-2161481|title=NME's Albums of the Year 2017 |work=[[NME]] |date=23 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|3}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qthemusic.com/articles/when-liam-met-ed-the-new-issue-out-on-tuesday|title=When Liam Met Ed... The New Issue, Out On Tuesday |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=21 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Visions of a Life'' debuted at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with 19,333 copies sold in its first week,<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=http://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/official-charts-analysis-shania-twain-takes-no-1-in-close-battle-with-wolf-alice/070064 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Shania Twain takes No. 1 in close battle with Wolf Alice |work=[[Music Week]] |date=6 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> becoming the band's second consecutive album to debut at this position.<ref>{{cite web |last=Copsey |first=Rob |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/shania-twain-wins-fiercely-fought-battle-against-wolf-alice-to-claim-her-first-number-1-in-18-years-on-the-official-albums-chart__20680/ |title=Shania Twain wins fiercely fought battle against Wolf Alice to claim her first Number 1 in 18 years on the Official Albums Chart |work=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=6 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> As of September 2018, the album had sold 57,214 copies in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paine |first=Andre |url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/we-won-a-mercury-this-is-mad-post-prize-sales-surge-for-wolf-alice/073896 |title='We won a Mercury, this is mad!': Post-prize sales surge for Wolf Alice |work=Music Week |date=21 September 2018 |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing  = Ellie Rowsell, Joff Oddie, Theo Ellis and Joel Amey\n| title1       = [[Heavenward]]\n| length1      = 4:55\n| title2       = [[Yuk Foo]]\n| length2      = 2:13\n| title3       = [[Beautifully Unconventional]]\n| length3      = 2:13\n| title4       = [[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\n| length4      = 4:35\n| title5       = Planet Hunter\n| length5      = 3:52\n| title6       = Sky Musings\n| length6      = 2:58\n| title7       = Formidable Cool\n| length7      = 3:33\n| title8       = [[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\n| length8      = 2:27\n| title9       = [[Sadboy]]\n| length9      = 4:11\n| title10      = St. Purple & Green\n| length10     = 4:21\n| title11      = After the Zero Hour\n| length11     = 3:24\n| title12      = Visions of a Life\n| length12     = 7:57\n| total_length = 46:39\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline     = Limited edition bonus 7-inch vinyl<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Visions of a Life |type=bonus 7-inch single |others=[[Wolf Alice]] |publisher=[[Dirty Hit]] |year=2017 |id=DH00229}}</ref>\n| collapsed    = yes\n| title13      = Yuk Foo\n| note13       = demo\n| length13     = 1:48\n| title14      = Bad Things\n| note14       = demo\n| length14     = 1:11\n| total_length = 49:38\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Visions of a Life''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Visions of a Life |type=liner notes |others=[[Wolf Alice]] |publisher=[[Dirty Hit]] |year=2017 |id=DH00213}}</ref>\n\n===Wolf Alice===\n* Ellie Rowsell \u2013 vocals, guitar, keyboards, [[Omnichord]], synthesisers\n* Joff Oddie \u2013 guitar, keyboards, programming, backing vocals, synthesisers\n* Theo Ellis \u2013 bass, keyboards, synthesisers, backing vocals\n* Joel Amey \u2013 drums, backing vocals, percussion, keyboards, programming, Omnichord\n\n===Additional personnel===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]] \u2013 production {{small|(all tracks)}}; keyboards, programming {{small|(track 6)}}; synthesisers {{small|(track 9)}}\n* [[Tom Elmhirst]] \u2013 mixing\n* Carlos de la Garza \u2013 engineering {{small|(all tracks)}}; additional percussion {{small|(tracks 7, 12)}}\n* [[Mike Schuppan]] \u2013 engineering\n* Tyler Shields \u2013 engineering assistance\n* [[Dave Cooley]] \u2013 mastering\n* Charlie Ellis \u2013 backing vocals {{small|(track 12)}}\n* Robert O'Hara \u2013 design\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Albums ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/10/aria-chart-watch-441/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #441|publisher=auspOp|date=7 October 2017|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n| 54\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|91|artist=Wolf Alice|album=Visions of a Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|133|artist=Wolf Alice|album=Visions of a Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=22 September 2018}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Ireland2|13|artist=Wolf Alice|rowheader=true|accessdate=22 September 2018}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Irish Independent Albums ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irma.ie/independent |title=Top 20 Independent \u2013 Week Ending 6 Oct 2017 |publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]] |accessdate=6 October 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20171006191501/http://www.irma.ie/independent |archivedate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n| 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Heatseeker Albums ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4408|title=NZ Heatseeker Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=9 October 2017|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n{{album chart|Scotland|2|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Spain|61|artist=Wolf Alice|album=Visions of a Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=22 September 2018}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|88|artist=Wolf Alice|album=Visions of a Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=11 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|2|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UKIndependent|1|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|190|artist=Wolf Alice|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardAlternative|25|artist=Wolf Alice|rowheader=true|accessdate=11 October 2017}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRock|39|artist=Wolf Alice|rowheader=true|accessdate=11 October 2017}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=Wolf Alice|artist=Visions of a Life|type=album|award=Silver|certyear=2018|relyear=2017|accessdate=7 October 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Wolf Alice}}\n\n[[Category:2017 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]\n[[Category:Mercury Prize-winning albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Wolf Alice albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Visions of a Life\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Wolf Alice]]\n| cover      = Wolf Alice - Visions of a Life.png\n| released   = {{Start date|2017|9|29|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Indie rock]]|[[indie pop]]|[[dream pop]]|[[psychedelic rock]]|[[shoegazing]]|[[post-punk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=46|s=39}}\n| label      = [[Dirty Hit]]\n| producer   = [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]\n| prev_title = [[My Love Is Cool]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n| type        = studio\n| name        = Visions of a Life\n| single1     = [[Yuk Foo]]\n| single1date = 12 June 2017\n| single2     = [[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\n| single2date = 5 July 2017\n| single3     = [[Beautifully Unconventional]]\n| single3date = 14 August 2017\n| single4     = [[Heavenward]]\n| single4date = 18 September 2017\n| single5     = Formidable Cool\n| single5date = 16 February 2018\n| single6     = [[Sadboy]]\n| single6date = 2 March 2018\n| single7     = [[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\n| single7date = 8 May 2018\n}}\n}}\n'''''Visions of a Life''''' is the second studio album by English [[alternative rock]] band [[Wolf Alice]], released on 29 September 2017 through [[Dirty Hit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2017/06/12/wolf-alice-yuk-foo-new-album-visions-of-a-life-2017-listen|title=Wolf Alice return! Hear 'Yuk Foo' from new album 'Vision of a Life'|work=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |last=Richards |first=Will |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The album received acclaim from music critics and appeared on several year-end lists, as well as winning the 2018 [[Mercury Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mercuryprize.com/news/see-the-2018-shortlist |title=See the 2018 Shortlist |work=[[Mercury Prize]] |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nIn November 2016, drummer Joel Amey said the band is \"very much in the middle of writing some new music.\" In May 2017, the band teased the album by sending mysterious postcards with song titles and lyrics of each of the album tracks to fans on their mailing list, which they later posted on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-sending-mysterious-postcards-fans-2078205|title=Wolf Alice are sending mysterious postcards to fans|work=[[NME]] |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> On 12 June, the band premiered the lead single \"[[Yuk Foo]]\" on [[BBC Radio 1]],<ref name=\"NME1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-announce-new-single-album-and-uk-and-world-tour-2087538|title=Wolf Alice announce new single 'Yuk Foo', second album and UK and world tour|work=NME |last=Daly |first=Rhian |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> with a lyric video being later uploaded to the band's [[Vevo]] channel on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eM75EQlDVLA|title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Yuk Foo (Lyric Video)|website=[[YouTube]] |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> They announced the release date of their upcoming album ''Visions of a Life'' would be on 29 September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/wolf-alice-announce-sophomore-album-visions-of-a-life-share-single-yuk-foo-listen|title=Wolf Alice announce sophomore album, Visions of a Life, share \"Yuk Foo\" \u2014 listen|work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |last=Kaye |first=Ben |date=12 June 2017 |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The band stated that the album is \"pretty varied\" and that they wanted to \"come out with a big bang,\" which is why they chose \"Yuk Foo\" as the first track to be released, adding that the rest of the album is \"pretty different to that.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BBCR1|number=874351394735697920|date=12 June 2017|title=\"We wanted to come out with a big bang\" @WolfAliceMusic are @AnnieMac's #HottestRecord with 'Yuk Foo' & tour news |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The band announced a world tour in support of the album with the dates being posted to the band's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wolfalice.co.uk|title=Wolf Alice|website=wolfalice.co.uk |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> The tour includes their biggest headline show to date at [[Alexandra Palace]] in [[London]] on 24 November.<ref name=\"NME1\" /> The album was produced by [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]].<ref name=\"NME1\"/>\n\nOn 5 July, the band released the second single \"[[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\", and made the album available for pre-order, along with the reveal of the album cover, which features a photo of lead vocalist Ellie Rowsell's aunt, Hellen, \"playing the classic game of 'dance round the horse's skull in your Sunday best'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-dont-delete-the-kisses-2098502|title=Wolf Alice release new single 'Don't Delete The Kisses' and share 'Visions Of A Life' album artwork|work=NME |last=Morgan Britton |first=Luke |date=5 July 2017 |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=wolfalicemusic|number=882647191499796480|date=5 July 2017|title=That's a photo of Ellie's aunty Helen playing the classic game of 'dance round the horse's skull in your Sunday best' |accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> The accompanying music video for \"Don't Delete the Kisses\" was released on 11 August.<ref name=\"Video\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WqxE-zppu30 |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Don't Delete the Kisses |website=[[YouTube]] |author=WolfAliceVEVO |date=11 August 2017 |accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> The third single \"[[Beautifully Unconventional]]\" was premiered on [[Annie Mac]]'s BBC Radio 1 show on 14 August, and was subsequently released for digital download and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/listen-wolf-alice-new-track-beautifully-unconventional-2124540 |title=Listen to Wolf Alice's new track, 'Beautifully Unconventional' |work=NME |date=14 August 2017 |first=Will |last=Butler |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> A 1950s-inspired music video was released on 11 September.<ref>{{cite web |last=Myers |first=Owen |url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/09/11/wolf-alice-beautifully-unconventional-video-premiere |title=Wolf Alice Get A Glamorous '50s Makeover in Their \"Beautifully Unconventional\" Video |work=[[The Fader]] |date=11 September 2017 |accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> The band released \"[[Heavenward]]\" as the fourth single on 18 September. The song premiered on [[Zane Lowe]]'s Beats 1 radio show, and subsequently released for digital download and streaming.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://diymag.com/2017/09/18/wolf-alice-heavenward-album-visions-of-a-life |title=Wolf Alice unveil 'Heavenward' from forthcoming album, 'Visions of a Life' |work=DIY |date=18 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> According to a press release, the song is about the death of a friend.<ref>{{cite web |last=Morgan Britton |first=Luke |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/wolf-alice-heavenward-2142334 |title=Stream Wolf Alice's personal new single 'Heavenward' |work=NME |date=18 September 2017 |accessdate=18 September 2017}}</ref> The album's fifth single, \"Formidable Cool\", was released on 16 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/formidable-cool-edit-single/1345743393 |title=Formidable Cool (Edit) \u2013 Single by Wolf Alice |work=[[iTunes Store]] (UK) |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> and was serviced to UK [[contemporary hit radio]] on 9 March 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist |title=BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Playlist |publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]] |accessdate=23 March 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310143326/http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist |archivedate=10 March 2018}}</ref> On 2 March 2018, \"[[Sadboy]]\" was released as the sixth single, followed by an accompanying music video three days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/sadboy-edit-single/1349917959 |title=Sadboy (Edit) \u2013 Single by Wolf Alice |work=iTunes Store (Canada) |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=WolfAliceVEVO |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6sRAzBWCnfM |title=Wolf Alice - Sadboy |work=[[YouTube]] |date=5 March 2018 |accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> \"[[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\" was released on 8 May 2018 as the seventh single.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Space & Time / Formiddable Cool |type=LP liner notes |others=Wolf Alice |publisher=[[Dirty Hit]] |year=2018 |id=DH00317}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on 30 May 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-wolf-alices-ellie-rowsell-become-runaway-bride-epic-space-time-video-2328628 |title=Watch Wolf Alice\u2019s Ellie Rowsell become runaway bride in epic 'Space and Time' video |work=NME |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n''Visions of a Life'' is primarily an [[alternative rock]]<ref name=\"Skinny\"/> and [[noise rock]] album,<ref name=\"RS\"/> and was noted by numerous critics to take influences from various genres, including [[shoegazing|shoegaze]], [[punk rock]], [[dream pop]], [[grunge]], [[psychedelic music|psychedelia]], [[contemporary folk music|folk]], [[space rock]], [[synth-pop]], [[hardcore punk|hardcore]] and [[electronica]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pearson |first=Rick |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/music/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-review-a3647286.html |title=Wolf Alice - Visions of a Life, review |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=29 September 2017 |accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"P4K\"/><ref name=\"IrishTimes\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.0/10<ref>{{cite web |title=Visions Of A Life by Wolf Alice reviews |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8941/Wolf-Alice-Visions-Of-A-Life.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 81/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |title=Reviews and Tracks for Visions of a Life by Wolf Alice |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/visions-of-a-life/wolf-alice |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |last=Phares |first=Heather |title=Visions of a Life \u2013 Wolf Alice |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/visions-of-a-life-mw0003076565 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = B+<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite web |last=Ihnat |first=Gwen |title=Wolf Alice's Visions Of A Life finds beauty in chaos |url=https://www.avclub.com/wolf-alice-s-visions-of-a-life-finds-beauty-in-chaos-1818840781 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web |last=Mumford |first=Gwilym |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life review \u2013 exuberant guitar-driven genre jumble |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/28/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-review |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite web |last=Clayton-Lea |first=Tony |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life album review: Londoners enter new chapter |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/album-reviews/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-album-review-londoners-enter-new-chapter-1.3230724 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cameron |first=Keith |title=Ahead of the pack |work=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |issue=288 |date=November 2017 |page=92}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last=Daly |first=Rhian |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 'Visions Of A Life' Album Review |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/wolf-alice-visions-life-review-2145110 |website=NME |date=27 September 2017 |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 7.0/10<ref name=\"P4K\">{{cite web |last=Monroe |first=Jazz |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life/ |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=2 October 2017 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Barton |first=Laura |title=Howling Success |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=378 |date=November 2017 |page=110}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web |last=Levy |first=Joe |title=Review: Wolf Alice Deliver Noise-Rock Seduction on Second LP |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-wolf-alices-visions-of-a-life-w506994 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=4 October 2017 |accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10score = 6/10<ref>{{cite journal |last=Richards |first=Sam |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=246 |date=November 2017 |page=39}}</ref>\n}}\nAt [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 81, based on 21 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\"/> Rhian Daly of ''[[NME]]'' called it the album of the year and claimed that \"with ''Visions of a Life'' Wolf Alice are removing any doubt about their status in the UK music scene. Best band in Britain? 100 per cent.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/> ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''{{'}}s Luke Beardsworth called the album \"a phenomenal achievement. It has captured on record the thrill, angst, sadness and uncertainty of being in your twenties and not really knowing what's going to happen or should happen. All of it is never anything less than intoxicating, heartfelt and effortless ... It feels like one of the most crucial, relevant, angry, cool and vibrant records of the decade. Wolf Alice, as fantastic bands tend to, have completely disregarded the idea that a second album should be difficult and turned out a genuine masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite web |last=Beardsworth |first=Luke |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/20085/reviews/4151372 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |date=26 September 2017 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s Heather Phares described the album as \"a reflection of a young band trying out all its possibilities,\" and thought it's \"more scattered than ''[[My Love Is Cool]]'', but its best songs hint at even more potential.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> ''[[The A.V. Club]]''{{'}}s Gwen Ihnat said \"In lesser hands, this kind of sonic disparity could be chaotic and confusing\u2014but with Rowsell's voice as the guiding light, ''Visions'' is a captivating, enjoyable ride.\"<ref name=\"AVClub\"/> Will Richards of ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' said, \"there's no difficult second album syndrome here. ''Visions of a Life'' is a gorgeously twisted beast that keeps Wolf Alice on the path to being Britain's best band.\"<ref name=\"DIY\">{{cite web |last=Richards |first=Will |url=http://diymag.com/2017/09/28/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life-album-review |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |work=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nMatt the Raven from ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]'' stated that the album \"may be a somewhat inconsistent journey but it's also pure rock and roll splendor from a band that's super talented and not afraid to take chances.\"<ref name=\"UTR\">{{cite web |last=the Raven |first=Matt |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/reviews/wolf_alice_visions_of_a_life |title=Wolf Alice: Visions of a Life Review |work=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]] |date=28 September 2017 |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>  ''[[Kerrang!]]'' stated that \"the eclectic sounds of Wolf Alice's debut made them stars, but this sequel finds them doing everything bigger and better.\"<ref name=\"MC\"/> Bella Spencer of ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]'' wrote, \"the album caters for all \u2013 there are heavy tracks for hardcore fans and songs with a more approachable indie feel for those who need a gentle introduction to the ways of the Wolf. So sit back, relax and scream to your heart's content.\"<ref name=\"Skinny\">{{cite web |last=Spencer |first=Bella |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life album review |url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |website=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] |date=25 September 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> In a more mixed review, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s Geoff Nelson thought that \"''Visions of a Life'' is often full, seeming to overflow. But the substance is lacking, resulting in a tiring trip through a band gamely trying not to merely cover itself.\"<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Geoff |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/album-review-wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |website=Consequence of Sound |date=22 September 2017 |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> In his rave review for ''[[musicOMH]]'', critic Craig Jones stated that \"there are no low points in this relentless record. At times it is beastly, baring its teeth. At others, it's divinely angelic\", continuing: \"So relevant and of its moment, touching on the little things which make up our lives then showing utter disdain to the establishment, you'll struggle to find many better albums than ''Visions of a Life'' this year.\"<ref name=\"MusicOMH\">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Craig |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/wolf-alice-visions-of-a-life |title=Wolf Alice \u2013 Visions of a Life |work=[[musicOMH]] |date=5 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''\n| Favourite Albums of 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|1}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4151506-drowned-in-sounds-favourite-albums-of-2017|title=Drowned in Sound's Favourite Albums of 2017|work= [[Drowned in Sound]] |date=22 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''RIOT Mag''\n| RIOT's Albums Of The Year 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|6}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riotmag.co/riots-albums-year-2017-top-10|title=RIOT's Albums Of The Year 2017|work=RIOT Mag|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| Albums of the Year\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|2}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/nmes-albums-of-the-year-2017-2161481|title=NME's Albums of the Year 2017 |work=[[NME]] |date=23 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| {{center|2017}}\n| {{center|3}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qthemusic.com/articles/when-liam-met-ed-the-new-issue-out-on-tuesday|title=When Liam Met Ed... The New Issue, Out On Tuesday |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |date=21 November 2017 |accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Visions of a Life'' debuted at number two on the [[UK Albums Chart]] with 19,333 copies sold in its first week,<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=http://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/official-charts-analysis-shania-twain-takes-no-1-in-close-battle-with-wolf-alice/070064 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Shania Twain takes No. 1 in close battle with Wolf Alice |work=[[Music Week]] |date=6 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> becoming the band's second consecutive album to debut at this position.<ref>{{cite web |last=Copsey |first=Rob |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/shania-twain-wins-fiercely-fought-battle-against-wolf-alice-to-claim-her-first-number-1-in-18-years-on-the-official-albums-chart__20680/ |title=Shania Twain wins fiercely fought battle against Wolf Alice to claim her first Number 1 in 18 years on the Official Albums Chart |work=[[Official Charts Company]] |date=6 October 2017 |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> As of September 2018, the album had sold 57,214 copies in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |last=Paine |first=Andre |url=http://www.musicweek.com/talent/read/we-won-a-mercury-this-is-mad-post-prize-sales-surge-for-wolf-alice/073896 |title='We won a Mercury, this is mad!': Post-prize sales surge for Wolf Alice |work=Music Week |date=21 September 2018 |accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing  = Ellie Rowsell, Joff Oddie, Theo Ellis and Joel Amey\n| title1       = [[Heavenward]]\n| length1      = 4:55\n| title2       = [[Yuk Foo]]\n| length2      = 2:13\n| title3       = [[Beautifully Unconventional]]\n| length3      = 2:13\n| title4       = [[Don't Delete the Kisses]]\n| length4      = 4:35\n| title5       = Planet Hunter\n| length5      = 3:52\n| title6       = Sky Musings\n| length6      = 2:58\n| title7       = Formidable Cool\n| length7      = 3:33\n| title8       = [[Space & Time (song)|Space & Time]]\n| length8      = 2:27\n| title9       = [[Sadboy]]\n| length9      = 4:11\n| title10      = St. Purple & Green\n| length10     = 4: